{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-54","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-54","text":"BlobSidecarsByRoot deprecated protocol must be fully disabled after current_epoch >= FULU_FORK_EPOCH + MIN_EPOCHS_FOR_BLOB_SIDECARS_REQUESTS, and during transition period must only serve pre-Fulu blobs identified by root.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Similar to PROP-0047 but for the by-root variant. Consistent deprecation behavior across both variants is critical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Post-transition requests are minor resource waste. Inconsistent deprecation between by-range and by-root variants could confuse implementations.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-55","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-55","text":"max_blobs_per_block returned by get_blob_parameters(epoch) must be consistent across all client implementations for any given epoch. Formally: forall (client_A, client_B, epoch E): client_A.get_blob_parameters(E).max_blobs_per_block == client_B.get_blob_parameters(E).max_blobs_per_block.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-005","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-008","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-007:beacon_block_kzg_validation","nodes":["actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001","tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block/sidecar gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Cross-client inconsistency in epoch-dependent blob parameters is the primary consensus split vector for EIP-7892. An attacker can craft blocks at parameter-change epochs to exploit any divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Cross-client disagreement on max_blobs_per_block for the same epoch causes a consensus split: some clients accept a block that others reject, permanently forking the network.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: identify an epoch where two clients compute different max_blobs_per_block values and demonstrate the resulting consensus split."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-56","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-56","text":"The proposer lookahead (EIP-7917) must be deterministic across all client implementations. For the same beacon state S: forall (client_A, client_B): client_A.compute_proposer_for_slot(S, slot) == client_B.compute_proposer_for_slot(S, slot) for all slots in the lookahead window.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-009","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-022","covers":{"primary_element":"fork:SG-002:upgrade_to_fulu","nodes":["actor-beacon-node","actor-validator-set","actor-proposer"],"edges":["tb-010","tb-011"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation (proposer check)"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker publishes a sidecar with a proposer_index that is correct according to one client's shuffling but incorrect according to another's. This exploits cross-client proposer assignment divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Cross-client proposer assignment divergence means some nodes accept blocks/sidecars from proposers that other nodes reject, causing a consensus split at the first divergent slot.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate two clients computing different proposers for the same slot from the same state."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-57","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-57","text":"KZG commitment verification, inclusion proof verification, and KZG proof batch verification must be cryptographically sound: forall (sidecar S where verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch returns true): the data in S.column is consistent with the claimed S.kzg_commitments. No computationally bounded attacker can forge a sidecar that passes KZG verification with incorrect data.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-002","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-003:verify_data_column_sidecar_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is the fundamental cryptographic soundness assumption. If KZG verification accepts invalid data, the entire data availability scheme is broken. Implementation bugs in the KZG library are the primary attack vector."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"KZG soundness failure allows injection of arbitrary data that passes all verification, completely undermining data availability guarantees. Network-wide impact.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: forge a data column sidecar with incorrect data that passes verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-58","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-58","text":"DoS resistance in the gossip validation pipeline: structural validation checks (index bounds, empty check, max_blobs, length consistency) must be performed BEFORE computationally expensive operations (KZG proof verification, inclusion proof verification). The proposer signature check must occur before KZG verification to act as a cost gate.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-003","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:data_column_sidecar_gossip_validation","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If expensive KZG verification is performed before cheap structural checks, an attacker can trigger O(n) expensive operations with O(1) effort by sending structurally invalid sidecars."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect check ordering allows CPU exhaustion DoS by triggering expensive KZG verification on structurally invalid sidecars. Single-peer DoS that could degrade node performance.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Note: high-effort sustained single-peer DoS is out-of-scope. This is in-scope if a single packet triggers disproportionate CPU cost."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-59","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-59","text":"DataColumnSidecarsByRange must serve all sidecars of a block if any are included. Partial block responses (serving some columns but not others for the same block) must not occur for columns that the server has in storage.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-008:INV-004","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-008:data_column_sidecars_by_range","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Partial block responses could cause syncing nodes to conclude that some columns are unavailable when they are actually available, failing data availability checks."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Partial responses cause incorrect data availability conclusions on syncing nodes, potentially delaying sync or causing the node to reject valid blocks.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate a server returning partial columns for a block, causing the requester to fail data availability."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-60","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-60","text":"DataColumnSidecarsByRoot must respond with at least one sidecar if the server has any matching the request. The server must not silently drop valid, available sidecars from the response.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-009:INV-003","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-009:data_column_sidecars_by_root","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-004"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If a server silently drops available sidecars from its response, requesting nodes would conclude the data is unavailable, failing data availability checks."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Dropping available sidecars from responses degrades data availability for syncing nodes, potentially preventing them from completing sync.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate a server that has sidecars but returns empty response."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-61","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-61","text":"DataColumnSidecarsByRoot must not serve sidecars for blocks failing beacon-chain state transition. Even if the block data exists in storage, if the block would fail state transition, its data columns must not be served.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-009:INV-005","source_threat_id":"stride-013","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-009:data_column_sidecars_by_root","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-004"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker probes for blocks that failed state transition. Serving data for invalid blocks acts as an oracle and distributes invalid data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Information disclosure about invalid blocks in the server's database. Low impact as the data is from blocks that cannot be finalized.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-62","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-62","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must IGNORE (not REJECT) sidecars whose parent block has not yet been seen by the receiving node. These sidecars must be queued for re-validation when the parent block arrives.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-026","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_parent_seen","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker floods sidecars referencing different unseen parents, each requiring queuing. The IGNORE queue must be bounded to prevent memory exhaustion."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Unbounded IGNORE queue for unseen-parent sidecars allows memory exhaustion. Bounded queues may cause legitimate sidecars to be dropped during network congestion.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: flood node with sidecars referencing unique unseen parents, measuring memory consumption."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-63","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-63","text":"Information disclosure resistance for DataColumnSidecarsByRange: responses to out-of-range requests must return ResourceUnavailable(3) without revealing information about the node's storage policies, sync state, or stored data beyond the serve_range.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-010","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-008:data_column_sidecars_by_range","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker probes with out-of-range requests and analyzes response timing or content to infer storage state."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Information disclosure about node storage policies. Limited exploitability and no direct security impact on consensus or data availability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-64","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-64","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify that the sidecar's slot is within valid bounds: slot > compute_start_slot_at_epoch(store.finalized_checkpoint.epoch). Sidecars at or before the finalized epoch's start slot must return IGNORE (not REJECT), as they are stale but not malicious.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_finalized","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker sends sidecars for already-finalized slots. These should be IGNORED (stale data). If REJECTED, the sender is penalized for sending stale data, which could be exploited to penalize honest peers during reorgs."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Stale sidecar handling is a minor correctness issue. Incorrect REJECT instead of IGNORE could penalize honest peers during reorg recovery.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-65","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-65","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must REJECT sidecars whose parent block fails validation. If the parent is known but has failed validation (e.g., invalid state transition), the sidecar must be rejected, not ignored.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_parent_valid","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker sends sidecars for blocks known to be invalid. If these are IGNORED instead of REJECTED, they would be re-queued indefinitely, wasting resources."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect IGNORE instead of REJECT for invalid-parent sidecars causes infinite re-queuing, wasting resources and potentially filling the validation queue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: send sidecars for known-invalid parent blocks and show they are IGNORED instead of REJECTED."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-66","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-66","text":"The proposer_index in a data column sidecar must match the expected proposer for the slot based on the deterministic proposer lookahead (EIP-7917). If the proposer_index does not match and the shuffling is available, the sidecar must be REJECTED. Spoofing a valid proposer signature for a non-assigned slot must not be possible.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-009","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-022","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_expected_proposer","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node","actor-proposer"],"edges":["tb-011"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline (proposer sig)","Gossip validation pipeline (proposer index)"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker with access to a validator private key sends sidecars for slots where they are not the assigned proposer. The proposer verification must use the correct lookahead, not stale shuffling data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Accepting sidecars from non-assigned proposers allows proposer privilege escalation. An attacker could inject blocks/sidecars at any slot if their validator key is accepted regardless of assignment.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: send sidecar with valid signature but wrong proposer_index for the slot and show it is accepted."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-67","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-67","text":"BlobSidecarsByRoot deprecated protocol transition period serve_range must be bounded: [max(current_epoch - MIN_EPOCHS_FOR_BLOB_SIDECARS_REQUESTS, DENEB_FORK_EPOCH), FULU_FORK_EPOCH). Only blobs from pre-Fulu epochs within this range may be served by root.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker requests blobs by root for post-Fulu blocks or very old blocks. Consistent epoch boundary handling is critical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Deprecated protocol handling issue. Impact limited to resource waste or minor inconsistency in transition period responses.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-68","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-68","text":"Peers must not be penalized for requesting blob sidecars by root from FULU_FORK_EPOCH during the transition period. The deprecated BlobSidecarsByRoot protocol must degrade gracefully without peer scoring penalties.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-003","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Consistent with PROP-0049 for by-range variant. Both deprecated protocols must degrade identically."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Peer scoring penalties for deprecated protocol use during transition could fragment the network by disconnecting nodes running slightly older software.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate peer being penalized for legitimate deprecated by-root request during transition."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-69","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-69","text":"The DataColumnSidecarsByRange response count must not exceed count * NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS sidecars, where count is the requested number of slots. This provides an upper bound beyond the absolute MAX_REQUEST_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS limit.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-008:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-008:data_column_sidecars_by_range","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a tighter bound than MAX_REQUEST_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS for small count values. Both limits must be enforced."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Missing count-based upper bound could allow sending more sidecars than expected for the requested range, confusing response parsing on the receiver.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate response exceeding count * NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS for a small count value."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-70","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-70","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify that the data column sidecar's inclusion proof correctly links kzg_commitments to the block body via verify_data_column_sidecar_inclusion_proof. Failure of the inclusion proof check must result in REJECT.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-025","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_inclusion_proof","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker crafts a sidecar with an invalid inclusion proof that appears structurally valid. If the inclusion proof check is bypassable or uses wrong parameters, arbitrary data columns could be injected."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Bypassing inclusion proof verification allows injection of data columns not committed in any valid block, undermining data availability guarantees.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: craft sidecar with invalid inclusion proof that passes verification."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B13-71","property":{"id":"PROP-W4B13-71","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify KZG proofs for data column sidecars via verify_data_column_sidecar_kzg_proofs. Failure must result in REJECT. The KZG check must occur after structural validation and signature verification, but must not be skipped.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-002","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline (structural)","Gossip validation pipeline (signature)"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker modifies data column cells while keeping commitments and proofs valid-looking. If KZG verification is skipped or has implementation bugs, tampered data propagates."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Skipping or incorrectly implementing KZG proof verification allows tampered data columns to propagate through the gossip network, completely undermining data availability.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: craft sidecar with tampered column data that passes KZG verification."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B13_1770297426.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W4B5-1","property":{"status":"success","source_file":"outputs/01b_PARTIAL_W3B12_1770273241.json","_source_file":"outputs/01d_PARTIAL_W0B1_1770284080.json","properties_count":50,"severity_distribution":{"CRITICAL":20,"HIGH":20,"MEDIUM":6,"INFORMATIONAL":2,"LOW":2},"bug_bounty_scope":{"program_name":"Ethereum Fusaka Audit Contest","program_url":"https://audits.sherlock.xyz/contests/1140","inherited_from":"trust_model","in_scope_components":["Block Validation","State Transition","Consensus Logic","Execution Layer (EL)","Transaction Pool"],"out_of_scope_components":["JSON-RPC API","Beacon API","Infrastructure bugs"]},"properties":[{"id":"PROP-0001","text":"The RLP encoding of an Account MUST produce a tuple in the strict order (nonce, balance, storage_root, keccak256(code)). Any deviation in tuple ordering produces a distinct and incorrect encoding, causing consensus divergence on account state roots.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","State transition execution","Account storage update"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Account encoding is invoked during state transitions triggered by externally-submitted transactions. An attacker crafting transactions that modify account state (nonce, balance, code) can exercise this path. If the tuple ordering is wrong, the entire state root diverges from the canonical chain, causing a consensus split."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect RLP tuple ordering in encode_account would produce a different state root for all nodes running the affected implementation, causing a consensus split. This is a network-wide impact affecting chain finality.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an alternative tuple ordering produces a different state root accepted by the faulty implementation but rejected by the reference implementation."},{"id":"PROP-0002","text":"The input to encode_account MUST be a valid Account instance containing nonce (Uint), balance (U256), and code (bytes) fields. If any field is missing or of incorrect type, encode_account MUST raise an error rather than produce a partial or malformed encoding.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EVM execution","State transition"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker submitting a transaction that triggers contract creation or state modification exercises this code path. If an implementation passes a malformed Account object (e.g., missing a field), the encoding could silently produce incorrect output."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A malformed Account input that bypasses validation could produce an incorrect RLP encoding, leading to state root divergence. The impact is limited to implementations that fail to validate Account structure before encoding.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a code path where an invalid Account object reaches encode_account without prior validation."},{"id":"PROP-0003","text":"The storage_root parameter passed to encode_account MUST be exactly 32 bytes in length (Hash32). If storage_root has any other length, the RLP encoding MUST fail rather than encode a truncated or padded value.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EVM execution","Storage root computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The storage root is computed from the account's storage trie. If a bug in storage trie computation produces a non-32-byte root, and encode_account does not validate the length, the encoded account would be non-canonical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A non-32-byte storage root would produce non-canonical account encoding, causing state root divergence and consensus failure. While the storage root computation itself has validation, a bug there combined with missing validation here creates a critical path.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a scenario where a non-32-byte value reaches the storage_root parameter."},{"id":"PROP-0004","text":"The keccak256 hash of the account code MUST be computed over the raw code bytes, not over any encoded or transformed representation. forall (account): encode_account(account).contains(keccak256(account.code)) where the hash occupies the fourth tuple position.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Contract creation","Code deployment"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker deploying a contract with specific bytecode can exercise this path. If the code hash is computed over a different representation (e.g., RLP-encoded code instead of raw bytes), the resulting hash differs, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect code hash computation would cause every account with code to have a different state representation across implementations, leading to a consensus split on any block containing contract deployments or code-touching operations.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC should deploy a contract and show the divergent code hash between faulty and correct implementations."},{"id":"PROP-0005","text":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT MUST be a module-level constant that is frozen and immutable after construction. Any attempt to modify EMPTY_ACCOUNT.nonce, EMPTY_ACCOUNT.balance, or EMPTY_ACCOUNT.code after module initialization MUST raise an error.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-028","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:EMPTY_ACCOUNT","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT is used as a reference value throughout state transition logic. If it is mutable and an internal code path modifies it, all subsequent comparisons against EMPTY_ACCOUNT would be incorrect. While not directly attacker-triggered, a mutation could be triggered indirectly through state transitions initiated by attacker transactions."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"If EMPTY_ACCOUNT is mutable and becomes corrupted, the definition of an empty account changes globally, potentially causing accounts to appear non-empty or vice versa. This affects account existence checks, which are consensus-critical.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires internal mutation; not directly exploitable by external attacker, but could be a latent bug enabling other attacks."},{"id":"PROP-0006","text":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT MUST have nonce == Uint(0), balance == U256(0), and code == b''. These values MUST be exactly equal to their zero/empty equivalents, not merely falsy or default-initialized.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-028","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:EMPTY_ACCOUNT","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT is compared against actual account states to determine if an account is empty (for deletion under EIP-161). If any field deviates from the specification, empty account detection fails, affecting state pruning and gas accounting."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect EMPTY_ACCOUNT field values would cause incorrect empty account detection. This affects state cleanup (EIP-161) and could lead to state bloat or incorrect gas accounting, but the impact is bounded to correctness rather than fund safety.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},{"id":"PROP-0007","text":"The type alias Address MUST be exactly Bytes20 (20 bytes). Any value assigned to an Address-typed variable MUST be exactly 20 bytes in length. Truncation or padding MUST NOT occur silently.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Address","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-external-user"],"edges":["tb-014"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Address parsing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Addresses are present in every transaction (from, to fields). An attacker crafting a transaction with a malformed address that is silently truncated or padded could cause the transaction to target a different account than intended. In Python reference specs, type aliases do not enforce runtime constraints unless explicitly checked."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Silent truncation or padding of addresses could redirect transactions to unintended accounts, potentially enabling fund theft. While the reference spec uses Python type hints that may not enforce runtime constraints, production implementations must enforce the 20-byte constraint.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate an implementation where a non-20-byte value passes as a valid Address and causes incorrect behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0008","text":"The type aliases Root and VersionedHash MUST both be exactly Hash32 (32 bytes). Root values represent Merkle tree roots and VersionedHash values represent blob commitment hashes. Any value shorter or longer than 32 bytes MUST be rejected.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Root,VersionedHash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie","actor-blob-submitter"],"edges":["tb-019","tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Block validation","Blob verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"VersionedHash values appear in type-3 blob transactions and are validated against blob KZG commitments. Root values appear in block headers (state_root, receipts_root). If either alias accepts non-32-byte values, downstream Merkle verification or commitment checks could be bypassed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Non-32-byte Root or VersionedHash values could bypass Merkle proof verification or blob commitment checks, potentially enabling state root forgery or blob data manipulation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate a path where a non-32-byte value is accepted as Root or VersionedHash."},{"id":"PROP-0009","text":"The type alias Bloom MUST be exactly Bytes256 (256 bytes). Bloom filter values in transaction receipts MUST be exactly 256 bytes. Incorrect Bloom size would cause log filtering to produce incorrect results.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Bloom","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Receipt generation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Bloom filters are generated from event logs during transaction execution. While the Bloom itself is derived (not directly attacker-controlled), an incorrect Bloom size would cause receipt encoding differences and state root divergence."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect Bloom size would cause receipt encoding differences, leading to receipts_root divergence and consensus failure. However, Bloom values are computed internally rather than directly supplied by an attacker.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate that a non-256-byte Bloom value is produced and accepted in receipt encoding."},{"id":"PROP-0010","text":"The Authorization dataclass for EIP-7702 MUST include chain_id for replay protection. forall (auth: Authorization): auth.chain_id == CURRENT_CHAIN_ID || auth.chain_id == 0 (wildcard). An Authorization with a chain_id that does not match the current chain and is not the wildcard value MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.chain_id","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit EIP-7702 set-code transactions with arbitrary Authorization tuples. If chain_id validation is missing or incorrect, authorizations from one chain could be replayed on another chain, allowing an attacker to set code on an account without the owner's consent on the target chain."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing chain_id validation enables cross-chain replay attacks for EIP-7702 authorizations. An attacker could replay a legitimate authorization from one chain to set arbitrary code on the victim's account on a different chain, enabling fund theft.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate cross-chain replay of an EIP-7702 authorization that sets code on a victim account."},{"id":"PROP-0011","text":"The (y_parity, r, s) fields of an Authorization MUST form a valid ECDSA signature over the authorization tuple (chain_id, address, nonce). The recovered signer address MUST be the account owner. An Authorization with an invalid signature MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.signature","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature recovery","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit transactions containing Authorization tuples with forged signatures. If ECDSA verification is missing or flawed, the attacker could set arbitrary code on any account without the owner's private key."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing ECDSA signature verification for EIP-7702 authorizations would allow an attacker to set arbitrary code on any account, enabling complete fund theft for all accounts on the chain.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate setting code on an account without a valid signature from the account owner."},{"id":"PROP-0012","text":"The nonce field in an Authorization MUST match the current nonce of the authorizing account at the time of execution. forall (auth: Authorization, account: Account): auth.nonce == account.nonce. An Authorization with a stale or future nonce MUST be rejected to prevent replay attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.nonce","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Nonce verification","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can replay a previously valid Authorization tuple. If nonce checking is absent, a single authorization could be replayed indefinitely to re-set code on the victim's account, even after the victim has revoked the authorization by incrementing their nonce."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing nonce validation enables same-chain replay of EIP-7702 authorizations. An attacker who obtains any valid authorization (even one the victim intended to be one-time) could repeatedly set code on the victim's account, enabling persistent fund theft.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate replaying a valid authorization after the account nonce has been incremented."},{"id":"PROP-0013","text":"The extract_deposit_data function MUST reject any input data whose length does not equal DEPOSIT_EVENT_LENGTH (576 bytes) by raising InvalidBlock. forall (data: bytes): len(data) != 576 => extract_deposit_data(data) raises InvalidBlock.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_validate_len","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The deposit contract emits events with data that is processed by extract_deposit_data. While the legitimate deposit contract always emits 576-byte data, a malicious contract at a spoofed address or a compromised deposit contract could emit non-standard data. Additionally, if DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS filtering is bypassed, arbitrary event data could reach this function."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"If non-576-byte data bypasses the length check, the subsequent offset and size parsing would read from incorrect positions, potentially producing malformed deposit requests that corrupt the beacon state (e.g., invalid pubkeys, wrong amounts). This is a consensus-critical path.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate crafting a deposit event with non-576-byte data that passes validation or causes unexpected behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0014","text":"All five offsets in extract_deposit_data MUST match their expected constant values: pubkey_offset == PUBKEY_OFFSET, withdrawal_credentials_offset == WITHDRAWAL_CREDENTIALS_OFFSET, amount_offset == AMOUNT_OFFSET, signature_offset == SIGNATURE_OFFSET, index_offset == INDEX_OFFSET. Any mismatch MUST raise InvalidBlock.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_check_pubkey_off,q_check_wc_off,q_check_amt_off,q_check_sig_off,q_check_idx_off","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker controlling or spoofing the deposit contract could emit events with valid-length data but incorrect internal offsets. If offset checks are missing or incomplete, the function would extract deposit fields from wrong positions, leading to corrupted deposit data accepted by the consensus layer."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect offsets would cause deposit fields (pubkey, withdrawal_credentials, amount, signature, index) to be extracted from wrong byte positions. This could create deposits with swapped or corrupted fields, leading to consensus-critical state corruption in the beacon chain.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that omitting or weakening an offset check allows extraction of deposit data from incorrect byte positions."},{"id":"PROP-0015","text":"All five sizes in extract_deposit_data MUST match their expected constant values: pubkey_size == 48, withdrawal_credentials_size == 32, amount_size == 8, signature_size == 96, index_size == 8. Any mismatch MUST raise InvalidBlock.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_check_pk_size,q_check_wc_size,q_check_amt_size,q_check_sig_size,q_check_idx_size","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker emitting deposit events with correct offsets but incorrect sizes could cause over-read or under-read of deposit fields. Missing size checks would allow the function to extract fields of incorrect length, producing malformed deposit requests."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"If a size check is bypassed, the extracted field would have an incorrect number of bytes. A wrong pubkey size (e.g., 47 instead of 48 bytes) would create an invalid BLS pubkey that could pass some but not all validation steps, causing consensus divergence between implementations with different tolerance for malformed pubkeys.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a size mismatch passes validation and produces a deposit request with incorrect field lengths."},{"id":"PROP-0016","text":"The output of extract_deposit_data MUST be exactly 192 bytes, consisting of pubkey(48) + withdrawal_credentials(32) + amount(8) + signature(96) + index(8) concatenated in that exact order. forall (data: valid_deposit_data): len(extract_deposit_data(data)) == 192.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_concat","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit data extraction","Consensus layer ingestion"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The concatenated 192-byte output is passed to the consensus layer as a deposit request. If the output length differs from 192, the consensus layer would parse the deposit request incorrectly, potentially misaligning pubkey, withdrawal_credentials, amount, signature, and index fields."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-192-byte deposit request output would cause the consensus layer to misparse all deposit fields, potentially crediting deposits to wrong validators with wrong amounts. This is a consensus-critical and fund-safety issue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that the output differs from 192 bytes or that field ordering is incorrect."},{"id":"PROP-0017","text":"Every validation failure path in extract_deposit_data MUST terminate with an InvalidBlock exception. There MUST be no code path where invalid data passes silently or produces a partial result. The function follows fail-stop semantics.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-005","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_error_len,q_error_pk_off,q_error_wc_off,q_error_amt_off,q_error_sig_off,q_error_idx_off,q_error_pk_size,q_error_wc_size,q_error_amt_size,q_error_sig_size,q_error_idx_size","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If any error path silently returns instead of raising InvalidBlock, the calling function (parse_deposit_requests) would accumulate malformed deposit data. The program graph shows 11 error states, each leading to q_final via an InvalidBlock raise. All 11 paths must be verified."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A validation bypass (silent return instead of InvalidBlock) on any of the 11 error paths would allow malformed deposit data to enter the consensus layer, potentially corrupting validator registrations.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must identify a specific error path that fails to raise InvalidBlock."},{"id":"PROP-0018","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST only process logs emitted by DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS. forall (log in receipt.logs): log.address != DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS => log is skipped entirely.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":"INV-006","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_addr","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can deploy a malicious contract that emits events with the same topic signature as the deposit contract. If the address filter is missing or uses case-insensitive comparison incorrectly, fake deposit events from the attacker's contract would be processed as legitimate deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing the deposit contract address filter would allow an attacker to inject arbitrary deposit requests by emitting matching events from any contract. This enables creating fake validator deposits, potentially corrupting the beacon state and stealing future rewards.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a deposit event from a non-deposit-contract address is processed as a valid deposit."},{"id":"PROP-0019","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST only process logs whose first topic matches DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH. forall (log from DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS): (len(log.topics) == 0 || log.topics[0] != DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH) => log is skipped.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-018","source_invariant_id":"INV-007","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_topic","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the deposit contract has other events (e.g., withdrawal events), and the topic filter is missing, non-deposit events from the deposit contract would be processed as deposits, producing garbage deposit data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Processing non-deposit events as deposit events would produce corrupted deposit requests with fields extracted from wrong event data. If the deposit contract emits other events, this could create invalid deposits.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must show that a non-DepositEvent log from the deposit contract is incorrectly processed as a deposit."},{"id":"PROP-0020","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST process receipts in receipt_keys order and logs within each receipt in their original order. The order of deposit requests in the output MUST be deterministic and match the order in which the underlying transactions were executed in the block.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-020","source_invariant_id":"INV-008","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_iter_keys,q_iter_logs","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If deposit ordering differs between implementations (e.g., due to non-deterministic receipt_keys iteration), the resulting deposit_requests bytes would differ, causing the requests_hash to diverge. This is a consensus-critical ordering property. An attacker could craft blocks with multiple deposit transactions to expose ordering bugs."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic deposit ordering would cause different nodes to compute different requests_hash values for the same block, leading to a consensus split. This is directly exploitable by including multiple deposit transactions in a single block.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that two valid implementations produce different deposit orderings for the same block."},{"id":"PROP-0021","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST accumulate deposit data without gaps. The deposit_requests output MUST be a contiguous concatenation of all valid 192-byte deposit request outputs. forall (valid_deposits d1, d2, ..., dn): deposit_requests == d1 + d2 + ... + dn with no interleaving, padding, or omission.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-009","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_append","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the accumulation has gaps (e.g., due to a failed extraction that does not propagate the InvalidBlock exception), the deposit_requests bytes would be shorter than expected, causing the consensus layer to misalign deposit field boundaries for all subsequent deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Gaps in deposit accumulation would cause all subsequent deposits in the same block to be misaligned, corrupting multiple validator registrations simultaneously. The impact scales with the number of deposits per block.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must show that a gap in accumulation causes subsequent deposit fields to be misaligned."},{"id":"PROP-0022","text":"trie_get MUST return a non-None receipt for every key in receipt_keys. forall (key in block_output.receipt_keys): trie_get(block_output.receipts_trie, key) != None. If any key yields a None receipt, the block MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-021","source_invariant_id":"INV-010","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_get_receipt","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipts trie integrity"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker proposing a block with a corrupted receipts trie could cause trie_get to return None for a valid key. If parse_deposit_requests does not handle this case (e.g., calling decode_receipt on None), it could crash the node or silently skip deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A None receipt for a valid key indicates receipts trie corruption. If not handled, this could crash the node (DoS) or cause silent deposit omission (consensus failure). The attacker can trigger this via a malformed block proposal.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a block with a corrupted receipts trie that causes parse_deposit_requests to crash or produce incorrect output."},{"id":"PROP-0023","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST individually SHA-256 hash each request before feeding the digest into the outer hash. The two-level hashing structure MUST be: outer = SHA256(SHA256(request_0).digest() || SHA256(request_1).digest() || ...). Single-level hashing (SHA256 of concatenated requests) is NOT equivalent.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash,q_update","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Request hash computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The requests hash is included in the execution payload header. If an implementation uses single-level hashing instead of two-level hashing, it would produce a different hash for the same requests, causing consensus divergence. An attacker can trigger this by including any request-generating transactions in a block."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect hashing structure would cause the execution payload header to contain a different requests_hash, leading to consensus divergence between implementations using single-level vs two-level hashing. This affects every block containing requests.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an implementation using a different hashing structure produces a divergent requests_hash."},{"id":"PROP-0024","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST be order-dependent. forall (requests r1, r2): compute_requests_hash([r1, r2]) != compute_requests_hash([r2, r1]) (unless r1 == r2). Reordering requests MUST produce a different hash.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-012","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_iter","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Request ordering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If compute_requests_hash is order-independent (e.g., using XOR instead of sequential hashing), two implementations processing requests in different orders would produce the same hash despite having different request orderings. Combined with PROP-0020, this ensures deposit ordering is consensus-binding."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Order-independent hashing would allow block proposers to reorder requests without changing the hash, potentially front-running or reordering deposits for economic advantage while other validators compute the same hash.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate request reordering that produces the same hash due to order-independent computation."},{"id":"PROP-0025","text":"compute_requests_hash with an empty requests list MUST produce the SHA-256 digest of the empty input: SHA256('').digest() == bytes.fromhex('e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4649b934ca495991b7852b855'). This is the hash of nothing being updated into the hasher.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-013","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_return","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":["Block validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Blocks with no request-generating transactions will have an empty requests list. If the empty-input hash value is wrong (e.g., the implementation uses a different initial state or adds a length prefix), every requestless block would have an incorrect requests_hash."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An incorrect empty-input hash would cause consensus failure on every block that contains no requests. Since many blocks may have no deposits, this would be a persistent consensus split affecting a large fraction of blocks.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that the implementation produces a different hash for an empty requests list."},{"id":"PROP-0026","text":"The deposit contract address used in parse_deposit_requests MUST be the canonical DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS specified in the chain configuration. It MUST NOT be hardcoded incorrectly, read from an untrusted source, or vulnerable to address collision attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","source_threat_id":"stride-tampering-tb-015","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Chain configuration","Deposit contract verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the deposit contract address is misconfigured or can be overridden via external input, an attacker could redirect deposit processing to a contract they control, injecting arbitrary deposits into the beacon state."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"A wrong deposit contract address would cause either: (1) legitimate deposits to be ignored (DoS on staking), or (2) fake deposits from an attacker-controlled contract to be accepted (beacon state corruption, fake validator creation).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate misconfiguration or override of DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS leading to fake deposit injection."},{"id":"PROP-0027","text":"The DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH used in parse_deposit_requests MUST exactly match the keccak256 hash of the deposit event signature from the deposit contract ABI. An incorrect hash would cause all legitimate deposit events to be silently skipped.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-018","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":["Constant verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a hardcoded constant. If incorrect, it would cause a systematic failure to process deposits on the affected implementation. While not directly attacker-controlled, the impact is severe as it would prevent all staking deposits from being processed."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect event signature hash would silently skip ALL legitimate deposits, effectively breaking staking on the affected implementation. This would cause consensus divergence as other implementations correctly process deposits.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Not directly attacker-exploitable but would cause a consensus split if the constant is wrong in any implementation."},{"id":"PROP-0028","text":"forall (data: bytes, len(data) == 576): extract_deposit_data MUST either return exactly 192 bytes or raise InvalidBlock. There MUST be no third outcome (empty return, partial return, None, or exception other than InvalidBlock).","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004,INV-005","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_final","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This property combines INV-004 and INV-005 to ensure the function has exactly two possible outcomes. Any implementation bug that causes a third outcome (e.g., returning an empty bytes or a Python None) would corrupt the deposit accumulation in parse_deposit_requests."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A third outcome (neither 192 bytes nor InvalidBlock) would silently corrupt the deposit request stream, potentially causing cascading misalignment of all subsequent deposit fields.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a code path that reaches q_final without returning exactly 192 bytes and without raising InvalidBlock."},{"id":"PROP-0029","text":"The RLP encoding in encode_account MUST be deterministic. forall (account1, account2): account1 == account2 => encode_account(account1, storage_root) == encode_account(account2, storage_root). Two identical accounts with the same storage_root MUST produce byte-identical RLP encodings.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_encode","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","RLP encoding"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-deterministic RLP encoding would cause identical account states to produce different state roots across nodes. If any implementation uses non-canonical RLP encoding (e.g., different integer encoding, non-minimal length prefixes), the resulting state roots would diverge."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic RLP encoding would cause state root divergence on every block, leading to a persistent consensus split. This is a foundational invariant for Ethereum's state model.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate two identical accounts producing different RLP encodings."},{"id":"PROP-0030","text":"The EIP-7702 Authorization dataclass MUST be used exclusively for set-code transactions (type 4). It MUST NOT be valid in any other transaction type context. Implementations MUST reject Authorization tuples in non-EIP-7702 transaction types.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction type validation","EIP-7702 processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker could attempt to include Authorization tuples in legacy or EIP-1559 transactions. If the transaction type check is missing, the authorization processing logic might execute in an unintended context, potentially bypassing other validation checks."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Processing Authorization tuples in wrong transaction types could bypass transaction type-specific validation logic, potentially enabling unauthorized code setting or other unexpected behavior.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate Authorization processing in a non-EIP-7702 transaction type."},{"id":"PROP-0031","text":"The y_parity field of Authorization MUST be either 0 or 1 (U8 with domain {0, 1}). Any other value MUST be rejected during signature recovery. Implementations MUST NOT accept y_parity values > 1.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.y_parity","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature recovery"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can craft Authorization tuples with arbitrary y_parity values. If values > 1 are accepted, the ECDSA recovery could produce an unexpected public key, potentially recovering a different signer address."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"While invalid y_parity values would likely cause signature recovery to fail or produce an incorrect signer, some implementations might accept y_parity > 1 via modular reduction, potentially recovering a valid but incorrect signer address.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that y_parity > 1 leads to incorrect signer recovery."},{"id":"PROP-0032","text":"The r and s values of an Authorization MUST be in the range [1, SECP256K1_ORDER - 1]. Values of 0 or >= SECP256K1_ORDER MUST be rejected. Implementations MUST NOT perform modular reduction on out-of-range r or s values.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.r,Authorization.s","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit Authorization tuples with r=0, s=0, or values >= SECP256K1_ORDER. If these pass validation, the ECDSA signature recovery could produce degenerate results or match arbitrary accounts."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-range r or s values in ECDSA can lead to signature malleability or recovery of unintended signer addresses. In the context of EIP-7702, this could allow unauthorized code setting on victim accounts.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that out-of-range r or s leads to a valid-looking signer recovery."},{"id":"PROP-0033","text":"The receipts trie MUST be complete: for every transaction in the block, there MUST be a corresponding receipt in the trie. forall (tx_index in 0..len(block.transactions)-1): trie_get(receipts_trie, rlp_encode(tx_index)) != None.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-021","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_get_receipt","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipts trie verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"A block proposer could submit a block with a receipts trie that is missing entries. If receipt completeness is not validated before processing deposits, missing receipts could cause deposits from those transactions to be silently skipped."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An incomplete receipts trie would cause some deposit events to be missed, leading to consensus divergence between nodes that validate trie completeness and those that do not.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a block with a missing receipt that causes deposit omission."},{"id":"PROP-0034","text":"The decode_receipt function called in parse_deposit_requests MUST correctly decode the receipt and preserve all log entries with their addresses, topics, and data fields intact. Incorrect decoding would corrupt the deposit filtering logic.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_decode","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Receipt RLP decoding"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If decode_receipt misparses the RLP-encoded receipt (e.g., due to a bug in handling typed receipts or non-legacy receipt formats), the log entries could be corrupted or missing, causing deposit events to be silently skipped or misprocessed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Receipt decoding errors could cause all deposit events within the affected receipt to be missed or corrupted, leading to consensus divergence on blocks containing deposits in the affected receipt format.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a receipt format that causes decode_receipt to produce incorrect log entries."},{"id":"PROP-0035","text":"The offset validation in extract_deposit_data MUST read offsets as big-endian unsigned integers from the ABI-encoded event data. Endianness errors would cause all offset comparisons to fail, either rejecting all valid deposits or accepting invalid ones.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_read_offsets","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["ABI decoding","Endianness handling"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"ABI encoding uses big-endian for offsets. If an implementation reads offsets as little-endian, the offset values would be drastically different from the expected constants, causing either (1) all deposits to be rejected, or (2) offsets to coincidentally match incorrect constants, extracting data from wrong positions."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Endianness errors in offset parsing would cause systematic deposit processing failures. If offsets are read in wrong endianness, they would not match expected constants, rejecting all valid deposits on the affected implementation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an endianness error causes deposits to be systematically rejected or misprocessed."},{"id":"PROP-0036","text":"The concatenation order in extract_deposit_data MUST be exactly pubkey + withdrawal_credentials + amount + signature + index. Any reordering of these fields would produce a different 192-byte output that the consensus layer would parse incorrectly.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_concat","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction","Consensus layer ingestion"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The consensus layer expects deposit request fields in a specific order. If the EL concatenates them in a different order, the CL would parse the 192 bytes incorrectly, assigning the pubkey bytes to withdrawal_credentials, etc."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Field reordering in the deposit request output would cause the consensus layer to misassign all deposit fields, creating validators with wrong pubkeys, wrong withdrawal credentials, and wrong amounts. This is a consensus-critical and fund-safety issue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that field reordering causes the CL to parse deposits incorrectly."},{"id":"PROP-0037","text":"The SHA-256 implementation used in compute_requests_hash MUST conform to FIPS 180-4. Using a different hash function (e.g., keccak256), a different variant (e.g., SHA-224), or a non-conforming implementation would produce a different digest for the same input.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Using the wrong hash function would cause the requests_hash to differ from all other implementations, resulting in consensus failure on every block containing requests."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Wrong hash function causes a persistent consensus split on every block with requests. This is a catastrophic implementation error rather than an externally exploitable vulnerability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Implementation error; not directly attacker-exploitable but causes consensus divergence."},{"id":"PROP-0038","text":"The storage_root parameter in encode_account MUST be validated against the storage trie Merkle root. forall (account): encode_account(account, storage_root) implies storage_root == merkle_root(account.storage_trie). Using an incorrect storage_root would cause the account encoding to be inconsistent with the actual storage state.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-022","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","Storage trie computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the storage_root passed to encode_account does not match the actual Merkle root of the account's storage trie, the encoded account would have a wrong storage root, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"A mismatched storage_root causes the entire state root to be incorrect, leading to consensus failure. This can be triggered by any transaction that modifies storage.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a code path where storage_root diverges from the actual storage trie root."},{"id":"PROP-0039","text":"The hash collision resistance assumption for keccak256 used in encode_account MUST hold. If two different code bytecodes produce the same keccak256 hash, two accounts with different code would have identical RLP encodings, violating account uniqueness.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Keccak256 preimage resistance"],"bug_bounty_scope":"out-of-scope","notes":"This is a cryptographic assumption on keccak256. A practical collision would have catastrophic implications for Ethereum but is considered computationally infeasible. Breaking keccak256 is out of scope for the bug bounty program."},"exploitability":"theoretical","severity":"INFORMATIONAL","severity_justification":"Relies on the cryptographic hardness of keccak256 collision resistance. No practical attack is known. This is a foundational assumption, not a vulnerability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Cryptographic assumption; breaking keccak256 is out of scope."},{"id":"PROP-0040","text":"The SHA-256 hash collision resistance assumption in compute_requests_hash MUST hold. A collision in the inner SHA-256 (per-request hashing) would allow two different requests to produce the same digest, making them indistinguishable in the outer hash.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["SHA-256 preimage resistance"],"bug_bounty_scope":"out-of-scope","notes":"This is a cryptographic assumption on SHA-256. A practical collision or preimage attack on SHA-256 would be a breakthrough in cryptography. Out of scope for the bug bounty program."},"exploitability":"theoretical","severity":"INFORMATIONAL","severity_justification":"Relies on SHA-256 collision resistance. No practical attack is known. Foundational cryptographic assumption.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Cryptographic assumption; breaking SHA-256 is out of scope."},{"id":"PROP-0041","text":"In parse_deposit_requests, the log.topics array MUST be checked for non-empty length before accessing log.topics[0]. Accessing topics[0] on an empty topics array MUST NOT cause an out-of-bounds access or crash.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-007","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_topic","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Event log processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can deploy a contract at DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS (if address spoofing is possible) or an event with zero topics. If the topics length check is missing, accessing topics[0] on an empty array would cause an index-out-of-bounds error, potentially crashing the node."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An out-of-bounds access on log.topics would crash the node during block processing, causing a denial of service. If the crash occurs during consensus-critical processing, it could affect block finalization.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a log with empty topics from DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS that causes a crash."},{"id":"PROP-0042","text":"The authorization address field in Authorization MUST be a valid 20-byte Ethereum address (Address = Bytes20). It represents the code address that the authorizer wants to set on their account. An invalid or non-20-byte address MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.address","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Address validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can include an Authorization with a non-20-byte address. If accepted, the EIP-7702 code delegation would reference an invalid address, potentially causing undefined behavior when the delegated code is executed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"An invalid authorization address would cause undefined behavior during code delegation execution. The impact depends on how the implementation handles the invalid address (crash, wrong code lookup, or no-op).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a non-20-byte authorization address causes unexpected behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0043","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST process each request exactly once. No request MUST be hashed twice (which would effectively duplicate it) or skipped (which would effectively remove it). The iteration over the requests list MUST be exact.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-011,INV-012","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_iter","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the iteration logic has an off-by-one error (processing n-1 or n+1 requests instead of n), the resulting hash would be incorrect. This would cause consensus divergence for any block with a non-zero number of requests."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An off-by-one error in request iteration would cause the requests_hash to be incorrect for blocks with requests, leading to consensus divergence.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate an iteration error that produces an incorrect requests_hash."},{"id":"PROP-0044","text":"The nonce field in Authorization MUST be U64 (unsigned 64-bit integer). It MUST NOT overflow or wrap around. If the authorizing account's nonce exceeds U64_MAX, the authorization MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.nonce","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Nonce range validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"While U64_MAX is astronomically large and practically unreachable, implementations in languages without native U64 overflow protection (e.g., Python) must ensure the nonce comparison does not overflow."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"U64 overflow for nonces is practically unreachable. The property exists for completeness and to guard against implementation errors in languages with arbitrary-precision integers where U64 truncation might not be enforced.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Practically unreachable; U64_MAX transactions from a single account is infeasible."},{"id":"PROP-0045","text":"The chain_id field in Authorization MUST be U256 (unsigned 256-bit integer). However, chain_id == 0 is reserved as a wildcard meaning 'any chain'. Implementations MUST treat chain_id == 0 as valid on all chains, not as an invalid or default value.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.chain_id","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Chain ID verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If an implementation rejects chain_id == 0 as invalid, legitimate wildcard authorizations would fail. Conversely, if an implementation does not properly handle the wildcard semantics, it might apply chain-specific authorizations across chains."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect handling of chain_id == 0 wildcard could either deny legitimate authorizations (DoS on EIP-7702 users) or expand authorization scope beyond the user's intent.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate incorrect wildcard handling leading to denial or over-application of authorizations."},{"id":"PROP-0046","text":"In parse_deposit_requests, the address comparison log.address == DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS MUST be an exact 20-byte equality check. Case-insensitive comparison, checksum-based comparison, or any normalization MUST NOT be used, as Ethereum addresses are raw 20-byte values at the execution layer.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":"INV-006","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_addr","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the address comparison uses case-insensitive string comparison (e.g., comparing hex representations), an attacker might exploit case differences. At the EVM level, addresses are 20-byte values without case, but some implementations might convert to hex strings for comparison."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"In practice, EVM-level address comparison is byte-exact. However, implementations that convert to strings for comparison might introduce case sensitivity issues. The impact is either false positives (accepting non-deposit events) or false negatives (rejecting legitimate deposits).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate an address comparison implementation that incorrectly matches or rejects addresses."},{"id":"PROP-0047","text":"The extract_deposit_data validation checks MUST be performed in the exact order specified: (1) data length, (2) pubkey offset, (3) withdrawal_credentials offset, (4) amount offset, (5) signature offset, (6) index offset, (7) pubkey size, (8) withdrawal_credentials size, (9) amount size, (10) signature size, (11) index size. While reordering does not affect correctness, it affects which error message is raised first, which matters for consensus on error behavior.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-002,INV-003","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_validate_len through q_check_idx_size","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the validation order differs and the error behavior is consensus-relevant (e.g., if InvalidBlock carries different error codes that affect execution), reordering validations could cause consensus divergence on invalid deposits."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Validation ordering typically does not affect consensus because InvalidBlock always causes the block to be rejected regardless of the specific error. However, if error codes or gas accounting differ per error path, ordering could matter.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Low impact; validation ordering is typically not consensus-critical as all error paths produce the same outcome (block rejection)."},{"id":"PROP-0048","text":"encode_account MUST handle the edge case where code is empty (b''). keccak256(b'') MUST produce the well-known empty code hash 0xc5d2460186f7233c927e7db2dcc703c0e500b653ca82273b7bfad8045d85a470. Incorrect handling of empty code would cause all code-less accounts to have wrong state roots.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","Code hash computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Every externally-owned account (EOA) has empty code. If the empty code hash is incorrect, every EOA's account encoding would differ, causing state root divergence on every block that creates or modifies an EOA."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect empty code hash would affect every EOA on the chain, causing a catastrophic state root divergence affecting virtually every block. This is one of the most impactful possible bugs.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate the wrong empty code hash causing state root divergence."},{"id":"PROP-0049","text":"The RLP encoding in encode_account MUST use canonical RLP: integers MUST use minimal-length big-endian encoding (no leading zeros except for the value 0 which is encoded as empty bytes), and the tuple MUST use the list encoding prefix.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_encode","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["RLP encoding","State root computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-canonical RLP encoding (e.g., using leading zeros in integer encoding or non-minimal length prefixes) would produce a different byte sequence for the same account, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-canonical RLP would cause state root divergence for every account, affecting every block. This is a foundational encoding invariant for Ethereum.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate non-canonical RLP producing a different state root."},{"id":"PROP-0050","text":"The two-level hashing in compute_requests_hash MUST prevent length-extension attacks. Because each request is individually hashed before being fed into the outer hash, an attacker cannot extend a valid requests_hash with additional requests. The property holds: forall (requests R, additional A): compute_requests_hash(R) cannot be extended to compute_requests_hash(R + A) without recomputing from scratch.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash,q_update,q_return","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Requests hash verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"SHA-256 is vulnerable to length-extension attacks on single-level hashing. The two-level structure (hash each request individually, then hash the digests) mitigates this. If an implementation uses single-level hashing, length-extension attacks could allow forging requests_hash values."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"If single-level hashing is used instead of two-level, length-extension attacks could allow an attacker to append requests to a valid block's requests list while keeping the same requests_hash, potentially injecting unauthorized deposits or withdrawals.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a length-extension attack on a single-level hashing implementation."}],"metadata":{"timestamp":"2026-02-05T00:00:00Z","total_properties":50,"by_type":{"invariant":25,"pre-condition":14,"post-condition":6,"assumption":5},"by_severity":{"CRITICAL":16,"HIGH":20,"MEDIUM":8,"LOW":3,"INFORMATIONAL":3},"by_scope":{"in_scope":44,"out_of_scope":3,"conditional":3},"by_reachability":{"external-reachable":40,"internal-only":7,"api-only":0,"theoretical":3},"bug_bounty_eligible_count":38,"coverage":{"subgraphs_covered":{"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)":["PROP-0001","PROP-0002","PROP-0003","PROP-0004","PROP-0029","PROP-0038","PROP-0039","PROP-0048","PROP-0049"],"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)":["PROP-0005","PROP-0006"],"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)":["PROP-0007","PROP-0008","PROP-0009"],"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)":["PROP-0010","PROP-0011","PROP-0012","PROP-0030","PROP-0031","PROP-0032","PROP-0042","PROP-0044","PROP-0045"],"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)":["PROP-0013","PROP-0014","PROP-0015","PROP-0016","PROP-0017","PROP-0028","PROP-0035","PROP-0036","PROP-0047"],"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)":["PROP-0018","PROP-0019","PROP-0020","PROP-0021","PROP-0022","PROP-0026","PROP-0027","PROP-0033","PROP-0034","PROP-0041","PROP-0046"],"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)":["PROP-0023","PROP-0024","PROP-0025","PROP-0037","PROP-0040","PROP-0043","PROP-0050"]},"trust_boundaries_covered":["tb-014","tb-016","tb-018","tb-019","tb-020"],"assumptions_covered":["asm-017","asm-018","asm-019","asm-020","asm-021","asm-022","asm-023","asm-024","asm-025","asm-026","asm-027","asm-028","asm-029"],"invariants_covered":["fork_types/SG-001:INV-001","fork_types/SG-001:INV-002","fork_types/SG-001:INV-003","fork_types/SG-002:INV-001","fork_types/SG-002:INV-002","fork_types/SG-003:INV-001","fork_types/SG-003:INV-002","fork_types/SG-003:INV-003","fork_types/SG-004:INV-001","fork_types/SG-004:INV-002","fork_types/SG-004:INV-003","fork_types/SG-004:INV-004","requests/SG-001:INV-001","requests/SG-001:INV-002","requests/SG-001:INV-003","requests/SG-001:INV-004","requests/SG-001:INV-005","requests/SG-002:INV-006","requests/SG-002:INV-007","requests/SG-002:INV-008","requests/SG-002:INV-009","requests/SG-002:INV-010","requests/SG-003:INV-011","requests/SG-003:INV-012","requests/SG-003:INV-013"]},"quality_checklist":{"all_properties_have_reachability":true,"all_properties_have_severity":true,"all_properties_have_exploitability":true,"all_properties_have_bug_bounty_eligible":true,"all_boundary_edges_covered":true,"properties_prioritized_by_scope":true,"metadata_includes_statistics":true}},"id":"PROP-W4B5-1"},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W4B5_1770297304.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-1","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-1","text":"bytes_to_bls_field MUST reject any deserialized integer value that is greater than or equal to BLS_MODULUS. Accepting out-of-range values would produce invalid field elements, corrupting all downstream polynomial arithmetic, cell computation, and KZG proof generation.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-002","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-002","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:cell_to_coset_evals","nodes":["actor-blob-submitter","actor-block-proposer","actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-001","tb-002","tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Blob size check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit blob data via type-3 transactions or send crafted cells via P2P gossip. Blob bytes are deserialized into field elements via bytes_to_bls_field in cell_to_coset_evals (SG-001). If the range check is missing, modular reduction silently corrupts data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Violation allows an attacker to inject invalid field elements into the polynomial commitment pipeline. This corrupts KZG proofs and cells, potentially causing consensus failures where valid-looking but incorrect data passes verification across the entire network.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating that an out-of-range blob byte sequence produces a cell that passes verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch but commits to incorrect data."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-2","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-2","text":"The Fiat-Shamir challenge computation in compute_verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_challenge (SG-006) MUST include ALL of the following in the hash input in canonical deterministic order: (1) RANDOM_CHALLENGE_KZG_CELL_BATCH_DOMAIN, (2) FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_BLOB, (3) FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL, (4) len(commitments), (5) len(cell_indices), (6) all commitments, (7) for each k: commitment_indices[k], cell_indices[k], all coset_eval bytes, proofs[k]. Omitting any element breaks Fiat-Shamir soundness.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-003","source_invariant_id":"SG-006:INV-001","source_threat_id":"stride-003","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-006:compute_verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_challenge","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-008"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker sends crafted data column sidecars via P2P. If any verifier-relevant data is omitted from the Fiat-Shamir hash, the attacker can manipulate the omitted field while keeping the challenge r unchanged, allowing proof forgery."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Violation of Fiat-Shamir completeness breaks the soundness of the entire batch verification scheme. An attacker could forge KZG proofs that pass verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch, undermining data availability guarantees network-wide.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing a forged proof that passes batch verification due to missing Fiat-Shamir binding. This is a consensus-level vulnerability."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-3","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-3","text":"The RANDOM_CHALLENGE_KZG_CELL_BATCH_DOMAIN separator used in compute_verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_challenge (SG-006) MUST be unique to this specific batch verification context and MUST NOT collide with domain separators used in any other protocol or verification context.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-003","source_invariant_id":"SG-006:INV-002","source_threat_id":"stride-023","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-006:compute_verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_challenge","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-008"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"A cross-protocol attack: if the domain separator collides with another protocol's domain, an attacker could construct a valid proof for one context and replay it in this context."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Domain separator collision could allow cross-protocol proof replay attacks, accepting proofs from unrelated contexts as valid batch KZG cell proofs.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a collision with another protocol's domain separator and a cross-context proof acceptance."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-4","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-4","text":"The hash input order in compute_verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_challenge (SG-006) MUST be deterministic and canonical across all implementations. Two honest nodes receiving the same (commitments, cell_indices, cosets_evals, proofs) MUST compute the same challenge r.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-006:INV-003","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-006:compute_verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_challenge","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-008"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-deterministic hash ordering would cause different nodes to compute different challenges, leading to inconsistent verification results and potential consensus splits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic Fiat-Shamir challenge computation would cause consensus splits: some nodes accept a proof while others reject it, partitioning the network.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating inconsistent verification results across two implementations due to ordering differences."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-5","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-5","text":"The universal verification equation in verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl (SG-015) MUST satisfy: e(LL, LR) == e(RL, [1]) where LL = g1_lincomb(proofs, r_powers), LR = KZG_SETUP_G2_MONOMIAL[n], and RL = RLC - RLI + RLP. A valid set of cells and proofs MUST always pass this check; an invalid set MUST fail with overwhelming probability (1 - 1/p).","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-015:INV-001","source_threat_id":"stride-020","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-015:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Length checks","Range checks"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Attacker sends crafted data column sidecars. The verification equation is the final cryptographic gate. If the random challenge r has insufficient entropy or the equation is incorrectly implemented, invalid proofs could pass."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing the verification equation allows an attacker to inject invalid cells that pass verification, breaking data availability guarantees across the entire network.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating acceptance of an invalid cell-proof pair by the batch verifier."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-6","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-6","text":"In verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl (SG-015), the random challenge r MUST bind all inputs via Fiat-Shamir. The challenge MUST have full entropy of the BLS scalar field (approximately 2^255 bits). hash_to_bls_field MUST produce a uniformly random BLS field element.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-015:INV-002","source_threat_id":"stride-020","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-015:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002","tb-008"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the challenge r has insufficient entropy (e.g., due to weak hash or truncation), an attacker can find inputs where individual proofs are invalid but the aggregated verification equation holds."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Insufficient entropy in the random challenge directly enables proof forgery in the batch verification scheme, a network-wide consensus failure.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires analysis of hash_to_bls_field output distribution and PoC showing bias exploitation."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-7","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-7","text":"The commitments list passed to verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl (SG-015) MUST contain no duplicates. Commitment deduplication in verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch (SG-021) MUST use byte-exact comparison, not hash-based comparison, to avoid hash collision attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-013","source_invariant_id":"SG-015:INV-003","source_threat_id":"stride-005","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-021:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Byte length checks"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker provides commitment_bytes over P2P. If deduplication uses a weak hash, the attacker could craft two semantically different commitments that map to the same deduplicated index, causing weight aggregation errors in the verification equation."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Incorrect deduplication causes the random linear combination weights to be wrong, potentially accepting invalid proofs or rejecting valid ones.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC with crafted commitment bytes that trigger deduplication errors leading to incorrect verification results."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-8","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-8","text":"All commitment_indices in verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl (SG-015) MUST reference valid entries in the deduplicated commitments array, i.e., forall k: commitment_indices[k] < len(commitments).","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-015:INV-004","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-015:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_impl","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Length checks"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Out-of-bounds commitment_indices would cause array index out-of-bounds access, potentially crashing the node."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-bounds array access could crash the validator node, causing single-node DoS.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating node crash via crafted commitment_indices."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-9","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-9","text":"In verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch (SG-021), all four input lists (commitment_bytes, cell_indices, cells, proofs_bytes) MUST have equal length. Mismatched lengths MUST cause the function to reject the input before any cryptographic operations.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-021:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-021:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Mismatched array lengths from P2P input could cause out-of-bounds access or incorrect verification. This is the first validation checkpoint."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Bypassing length validation could lead to out-of-bounds memory access or incorrect cryptographic results, potentially crashing the node.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing crash or incorrect verification result from mismatched input lengths."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-10","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-10","text":"In verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch (SG-021), each cell_index MUST be strictly less than CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB. Out-of-range cell_indices MUST be rejected before being used in coset_for_cell or coset_shift_for_cell.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-021:INV-004","source_threat_id":"stride-017","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-021:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Attacker sends cell_indices >= CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB via P2P. coset_shift_for_cell and coset_for_cell access roots_brp[FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL * cell_index], which would be out-of-bounds."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-bounds array access in coset_shift_for_cell or coset_for_cell could crash the node (segfault) or cause memory corruption, leading to single-node DoS.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating node crash from out-of-range cell_index in P2P data column sidecar."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-11","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-11","text":"In verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch (SG-021), each commitment_bytes MUST have length exactly BYTES_PER_COMMITMENT, each cell MUST have length exactly BYTES_PER_CELL, and each proof_bytes MUST have length exactly BYTES_PER_PROOF. Incorrect lengths MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-021:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-021:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Incorrect byte lengths from P2P could cause deserialization errors, buffer overflows, or incorrect field element parsing."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Accepting incorrectly-sized bytes could cause buffer overflows or incorrect deserialization, potentially leading to crashes or memory corruption.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating crash or unexpected behavior from malformed byte lengths."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-12","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-12","text":"bytes_to_kzg_commitment and bytes_to_kzg_proof MUST perform BLS12-381 G1 subgroup checks during deserialization. Points not on the correct subgroup MUST be rejected. Accepting non-subgroup points would cause the pairing check to produce incorrect results.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-024","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-021:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Byte length checks"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker provides commitment or proof bytes that deserialize to a point on the BLS12-381 curve but NOT in the correct G1 subgroup. Without subgroup checks, the pairing equation could give incorrect results."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing subgroup checks in pairing-based cryptography is a well-known class of vulnerability. It allows forging proofs that pass the pairing check, breaking data availability guarantees.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC with a non-subgroup point that causes the pairing check to accept an invalid proof."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-13","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-13","text":"In verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch (SG-021), commitment deduplication MUST preserve semantic equivalence: forall k: deduplicated_commitments[commitment_indices[k]] == original_commitment_bytes[k]. The mapping from original indices to deduplicated indices MUST be bijective on equivalence classes.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-013","source_invariant_id":"SG-021:INV-003","source_threat_id":"stride-005","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-021:verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Byte length checks"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An off-by-one in the commitment_indices mapping would cause weights to be accumulated against the wrong commitment in the verification equation."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Incorrect commitment-to-index mapping causes verification to aggregate weights incorrectly, potentially accepting invalid proofs.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating a batch with deliberately structured commitments that exploit an off-by-one in the mapping."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-14","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-14","text":"recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs (SG-024) MUST require at least CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB / 2 cells for recovery. If fewer than 50% of cells are provided, the function MUST reject the input. This threshold is mathematically required by the rate-2 Reed-Solomon erasure coding.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":"SG-024:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-024:recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Cell count check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker withholds cells so that fewer than 50% are available. If the threshold check is bypassed, recovery produces an incorrect polynomial."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Bypassing the 50% threshold produces a mathematically incorrect recovered polynomial, which then generates incorrect cells and proofs that propagate through the network.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing recovery with fewer than 50% cells produces incorrect output that is accepted downstream."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-15","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-15","text":"In recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs (SG-024), cell_indices MUST be unique and in ascending sorted order. Duplicate cell_indices MUST be rejected. forall i < j: cell_indices[i] < cell_indices[j].","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-024:INV-003","source_threat_id":"stride-019","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-024:recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker provides duplicate cell_indices with conflicting cell data. If uniqueness is not enforced, polynomial interpolation produces incorrect results, and the recovered polynomial differs from the original."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Duplicate cell_indices with conflicting cell data would cause polynomial recovery to produce an incorrect polynomial, leading to distribution of invalid data.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC with duplicate cell_indices and conflicting cells causing incorrect recovery."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-16","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-16","text":"In recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs (SG-024), all cell_indices MUST be in [0, CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB). Out-of-range indices MUST be rejected before polynomial recovery begins.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-024:INV-004","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-024:recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Out-of-range cell indices would cause out-of-bounds access in coset computation functions."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-bounds cell indices cause crashes in coset_for_cell and related functions, leading to single-node DoS.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating node crash from out-of-range cell_index during recovery."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-17","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-17","text":"After recover_polynomialcoeff (SG-023) produces a recovered polynomial, the caller MUST verify the recovered cells and proofs against the original KZG commitment. The recovery function itself does NOT verify commitment consistency. forall recovered_cell: verify_cell_kzg_proof(original_commitment, cell_index, recovered_cell, recovered_proof) == True.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-004","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-024:recover_cells_and_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation","Cell availability check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker provides corrupted cells for valid cell_indices. Without post-recovery commitment verification, the node propagates incorrect data to other peers."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Missing post-recovery verification turns a validator node into a vector for distributing invalid data. Other nodes trusting reconstructed data accept corrupted cells.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing a node distributing corrupted cells after recovery from attacker-provided data without commitment re-verification."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-18","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-18","text":"The recovered polynomial from recover_polynomialcoeff (SG-023) MUST have degree strictly less than FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_BLOB. The output poly_coeff[:FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_BLOB] truncation MUST not discard any non-zero coefficients above FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_BLOB.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-023:INV-003","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-023:recover_polynomialcoeff","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Cell availability check","50% threshold check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the recovered polynomial has degree >= FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_BLOB, the truncation discards non-zero coefficients, producing an incorrect polynomial."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect truncation produces wrong cells and proofs. However, this should be caught by post-recovery commitment verification.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating crafted cell data that causes the recovered polynomial to exceed the expected degree."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-19","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-19","text":"In recover_polynomialcoeff (SG-023), the element-wise division reconstructed[i] = ez_over_coset[i] / zp_over_coset[i] MUST NOT encounter division by zero. The vanishing polynomial Z(x) evaluated on the coset (shifted by PRIMITIVE_ROOT_OF_UNITY) MUST be non-zero at every point. forall i: zp_over_coset[i] != 0.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-008","source_invariant_id":"SG-023:INV-002","source_threat_id":"stride-016","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-023:recover_polynomialcoeff","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Cell availability check","50% threshold check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The coset shift by PRIMITIVE_ROOT_OF_UNITY ensures Z(x) has no roots on the coset. If the shift is incorrect, division by zero crashes the node."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Division by zero during recovery crashes the validator node. Although the root cause is an incorrect coset shift (implementation bug), the trigger is attacker-controlled cell withholding.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating a division-by-zero crash during cell recovery triggered by specific missing cell patterns."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-20","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-20","text":"The coset_fft_field (SG-005) shift_factor MUST equal PRIMITIVE_ROOT_OF_UNITY. An incorrect shift factor would cause the coset to coincide with roots of vanishing polynomials, enabling division by zero in recover_polynomialcoeff.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-008","source_invariant_id":"SG-005:INV-001","source_threat_id":"stride-016","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-005:coset_fft_field","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a constant correctness property. An incorrect PRIMITIVE_ROOT_OF_UNITY would be a fundamental implementation bug affecting all coset-based operations."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Incorrect shift factor causes systematic division-by-zero in all recovery operations, affecting every node running the incorrect implementation.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-21","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-21","text":"The bit-reversal permutation applied in polynomial_eval_to_coeff (SG-007), coset_for_cell (SG-017), and coset_shift_for_cell (SG-016) MUST correctly map between evaluation-domain ordering and the canonical ordering expected by FFT. forall i: brp(brp(i)) == i (involution property).","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-005","source_invariant_id":"SG-007:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-007:polynomial_eval_to_coeff","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-001","tb-002","tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Blob validation","Cell validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An incorrect bit-reversal permutation would produce wrong polynomial coefficients, leading to incorrect cells and proofs. This affects all blob processing and cell verification paths."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Incorrect permutation corrupts all polynomial conversions, producing incorrect proofs and cells that may or may not pass verification depending on the specific error.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a permutation implementation that produces incorrect polynomial coefficients."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-22","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-22","text":"In divide_polynomialcoeff (SG-010), the divisor polynomial b MUST NOT be the zero polynomial, and its leading coefficient b[bpos] MUST be nonzero. Division by zero polynomial MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-007","source_invariant_id":"SG-010:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-010:divide_polynomialcoeff","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Cell availability check","50% threshold"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The divisor polynomial is the vanishing polynomial constructed from missing cell roots. If all cells are present (no missing roots), the vanishing polynomial is the constant 1, which is valid. However, edge cases in construction could produce a zero polynomial."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Division by zero polynomial crashes the node during proof generation or polynomial recovery.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing a set of missing cell indices that produces a zero vanishing polynomial."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-23","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-23","text":"In interpolate_polynomialcoeff (SG-011), all xs values MUST be distinct. forall i != j: xs[i] != xs[j]. Duplicate xs values would cause (xs[i] - xs[j]).inverse() to attempt inverting zero, resulting in a crash.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-011","source_invariant_id":"SG-011:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-011:interpolate_polynomialcoeff","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002","tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Cell index validation","Coset computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The xs values are coset points derived from cell_indices. If duplicate cell_indices slip through validation, duplicate coset points would be passed to interpolation, causing a crash."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Division by zero in Lagrange interpolation crashes the validator node, causing single-node DoS.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing a crash in interpolation triggered by duplicate cell_indices that bypass validation."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-24","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-24","text":"In multiply_polynomialcoeff (SG-009), len(a) + len(b) MUST be <= FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_EXT_BLOB. This prevents the product polynomial from exceeding the extended evaluation domain, which would cause incorrect FFT results.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"SG-009:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-009:multiply_polynomialcoeff","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-001","tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Blob size check","Cell count check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The assertion prevents buffer overflow during polynomial multiplication. If many cells are missing (close to 50%), the vanishing polynomial can be large, and the product with another polynomial could exceed bounds."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Assertion bypass causes buffer overflow or incorrect polynomial arithmetic. Impact depends on memory safety of the implementation language.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating assertion bypass with specific missing cell patterns."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-25","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-25","text":"In coset_shift_for_cell (SG-016), cell_index MUST be in [0, CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB). The assertion MUST be enforced before computing roots_brp[FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL * cell_index].","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-016:INV-001","source_threat_id":"stride-017","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-016:coset_shift_for_cell","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Attacker-controlled cell_index from P2P input. FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL * cell_index could overflow or exceed array bounds."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-bounds array access crashes the node or causes memory corruption.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC showing node crash from crafted cell_index."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-26","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-26","text":"In coset_for_cell (SG-017), cell_index MUST be in [0, CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB), and the returned Coset MUST have exactly FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL elements. The slice roots_brp[start : start + FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL] MUST be in bounds.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-017:INV-001","source_threat_id":"stride-017","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-017:coset_for_cell","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["P2P gossip validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Same as PROP-0025 but for the full coset retrieval."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-bounds slice access causes crashes or returns incorrect coset elements.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Same as PROP-0025."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-27","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-27","text":"cell_to_coset_evals (SG-001) MUST produce a CosetEvals with exactly FIELD_ELEMENTS_PER_CELL elements. Each cell byte segment [i*BYTES_PER_FIELD_ELEMENT : (i+1)*BYTES_PER_FIELD_ELEMENT] MUST be exactly BYTES_PER_FIELD_ELEMENT bytes.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-001:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:cell_to_coset_evals","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-002"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Cell byte length check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Cells received via P2P are deserialized. If the cell is shorter than expected, byte slicing produces undersized field element bytes."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect field element count produces wrong coset evaluations, potentially causing verification errors.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC with malformed cell bytes."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-28","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-28","text":"coset_evals_to_cell (SG-002) is the exact inverse of cell_to_coset_evals (SG-001) for valid field elements. forall valid cell: coset_evals_to_cell(cell_to_coset_evals(cell)) == cell.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-002:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:coset_evals_to_cell","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Roundtrip property. If violated, recovered cells differ from originals even with correct polynomial."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Broken roundtrip causes recovered cells to differ from originals, producing invalid sidecars.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-29","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-29","text":"The _fft_field (SG-003) MUST require len(vals) to be a power of 2 and len(vals) == len(roots_of_unity). Non-power-of-2 inputs MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-003:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:_fft_field","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"FFT requires power-of-2 sizes for correctness. Non-power-of-2 sizes cause incorrect butterfly operations."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect FFT results propagate to all polynomial operations, producing wrong cells and proofs.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-30","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-30","text":"fft_field (SG-004) inverse FFT MUST correctly apply the normalization factor 1/N: forall polynomial p: ifft(fft(p)) == p. The inverse FFT MUST reverse the roots_of_unity order (except the first element).","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-004:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:fft_field","nodes":["actor-validator-node"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The inverse FFT is used in polynomial_eval_to_coeff and recover_polynomialcoeff. Incorrect normalization produces wrong coefficients."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Incorrect FFT normalization corrupts all polynomial coefficient computations, affecting proofs and recovery.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}
{"property_id":"PROP-W5B14-31","property":{"id":"PROP-W5B14-31","text":"compute_cells_and_kzg_proofs (SG-020) MUST accept only blobs of exactly BYTES_PER_BLOB bytes. The output MUST contain exactly CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB cells and CELLS_PER_EXT_BLOB proofs.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"SG-020:INV-002","source_threat_id":"stride-014","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-020:compute_cells_and_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-blob-submitter","actor-block-proposer"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Blob size check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"A blob submitter provides blob bytes via type-3 transaction. Incorrect blob size must be rejected before polynomial operations."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect blob sizes cause incorrect polynomial representations, but should be caught by earlier transaction validation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC with a blob that bypasses size validation."},"source_file":"outputs/01e_PARTIAL_W5B14_1770297294.json"}

{"id":"PROP-W4B13-65","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must REJECT sidecars whose parent block fails validation. If the parent is known but has failed validation (e.g., invalid state transition), the sidecar must be rejected, not ignored.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_parent_valid","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker sends sidecars for blocks known to be invalid. If these are IGNORED instead of REJECTED, they would be re-queued indefinitely, wasting resources."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect IGNORE instead of REJECT for invalid-parent sidecars causes infinite re-queuing, wasting resources and potentially filling the validation queue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: send sidecars for known-invalid parent blocks and show they are IGNORED instead of REJECTED."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-66","text":"The proposer_index in a data column sidecar must match the expected proposer for the slot based on the deterministic proposer lookahead (EIP-7917). If the proposer_index does not match and the shuffling is available, the sidecar must be REJECTED. Spoofing a valid proposer signature for a non-assigned slot must not be possible.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-009","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-022","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_expected_proposer","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node","actor-proposer"],"edges":["tb-011"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline (proposer sig)","Gossip validation pipeline (proposer index)"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker with access to a validator private key sends sidecars for slots where they are not the assigned proposer. The proposer verification must use the correct lookahead, not stale shuffling data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Accepting sidecars from non-assigned proposers allows proposer privilege escalation. An attacker could inject blocks/sidecars at any slot if their validator key is accepted regardless of assignment.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: send sidecar with valid signature but wrong proposer_index for the slot and show it is accepted."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-67","text":"BlobSidecarsByRoot deprecated protocol transition period serve_range must be bounded: [max(current_epoch - MIN_EPOCHS_FOR_BLOB_SIDECARS_REQUESTS, DENEB_FORK_EPOCH), FULU_FORK_EPOCH). Only blobs from pre-Fulu epochs within this range may be served by root.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker requests blobs by root for post-Fulu blocks or very old blocks. Consistent epoch boundary handling is critical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Deprecated protocol handling issue. Impact limited to resource waste or minor inconsistency in transition period responses.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-68","text":"Peers must not be penalized for requesting blob sidecars by root from FULU_FORK_EPOCH during the transition period. The deprecated BlobSidecarsByRoot protocol must degrade gracefully without peer scoring penalties.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-003","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Consistent with PROP-0049 for by-range variant. Both deprecated protocols must degrade identically."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Peer scoring penalties for deprecated protocol use during transition could fragment the network by disconnecting nodes running slightly older software.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate peer being penalized for legitimate deprecated by-root request during transition."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-69","text":"The DataColumnSidecarsByRange response count must not exceed count * NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS sidecars, where count is the requested number of slots. This provides an upper bound beyond the absolute MAX_REQUEST_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS limit.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-008:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-008:data_column_sidecars_by_range","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a tighter bound than MAX_REQUEST_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS for small count values. Both limits must be enforced."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Missing count-based upper bound could allow sending more sidecars than expected for the requested range, confusing response parsing on the receiver.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate response exceeding count * NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS for a small count value."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-70","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify that the data column sidecar's inclusion proof correctly links kzg_commitments to the block body via verify_data_column_sidecar_inclusion_proof. Failure of the inclusion proof check must result in REJECT.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-025","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_inclusion_proof","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker crafts a sidecar with an invalid inclusion proof that appears structurally valid. If the inclusion proof check is bypassable or uses wrong parameters, arbitrary data columns could be injected."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Bypassing inclusion proof verification allows injection of data columns not committed in any valid block, undermining data availability guarantees.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: craft sidecar with invalid inclusion proof that passes verification."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-71","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify KZG proofs for data column sidecars via verify_data_column_sidecar_kzg_proofs. Failure must result in REJECT. The KZG check must occur after structural validation and signature verification, but must not be skipped.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-002","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline (structural)","Gossip validation pipeline (signature)"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker modifies data column cells while keeping commitments and proofs valid-looking. If KZG verification is skipped or has implementation bugs, tampered data propagates."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Skipping or incorrectly implementing KZG proof verification allows tampered data columns to propagate through the gossip network, completely undermining data availability.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: craft sidecar with tampered column data that passes KZG verification."}
{"status":"success","source_file":"outputs/01b_PARTIAL_W3B12_1770273241.json","_source_file":"outputs/01d_PARTIAL_W0B1_1770284080.json","properties_count":50,"severity_distribution":{"CRITICAL":20,"HIGH":20,"MEDIUM":6,"INFORMATIONAL":2,"LOW":2},"bug_bounty_scope":{"program_name":"Ethereum Fusaka Audit Contest","program_url":"https://audits.sherlock.xyz/contests/1140","inherited_from":"trust_model","in_scope_components":["Block Validation","State Transition","Consensus Logic","Execution Layer (EL)","Transaction Pool"],"out_of_scope_components":["JSON-RPC API","Beacon API","Infrastructure bugs"]},"properties":[{"id":"PROP-0001","text":"The RLP encoding of an Account MUST produce a tuple in the strict order (nonce, balance, storage_root, keccak256(code)). Any deviation in tuple ordering produces a distinct and incorrect encoding, causing consensus divergence on account state roots.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","State transition execution","Account storage update"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Account encoding is invoked during state transitions triggered by externally-submitted transactions. An attacker crafting transactions that modify account state (nonce, balance, code) can exercise this path. If the tuple ordering is wrong, the entire state root diverges from the canonical chain, causing a consensus split."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect RLP tuple ordering in encode_account would produce a different state root for all nodes running the affected implementation, causing a consensus split. This is a network-wide impact affecting chain finality.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an alternative tuple ordering produces a different state root accepted by the faulty implementation but rejected by the reference implementation."},{"id":"PROP-0002","text":"The input to encode_account MUST be a valid Account instance containing nonce (Uint), balance (U256), and code (bytes) fields. If any field is missing or of incorrect type, encode_account MUST raise an error rather than produce a partial or malformed encoding.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EVM execution","State transition"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker submitting a transaction that triggers contract creation or state modification exercises this code path. If an implementation passes a malformed Account object (e.g., missing a field), the encoding could silently produce incorrect output."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A malformed Account input that bypasses validation could produce an incorrect RLP encoding, leading to state root divergence. The impact is limited to implementations that fail to validate Account structure before encoding.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a code path where an invalid Account object reaches encode_account without prior validation."},{"id":"PROP-0003","text":"The storage_root parameter passed to encode_account MUST be exactly 32 bytes in length (Hash32). If storage_root has any other length, the RLP encoding MUST fail rather than encode a truncated or padded value.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EVM execution","Storage root computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The storage root is computed from the account's storage trie. If a bug in storage trie computation produces a non-32-byte root, and encode_account does not validate the length, the encoded account would be non-canonical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A non-32-byte storage root would produce non-canonical account encoding, causing state root divergence and consensus failure. While the storage root computation itself has validation, a bug there combined with missing validation here creates a critical path.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a scenario where a non-32-byte value reaches the storage_root parameter."},{"id":"PROP-0004","text":"The keccak256 hash of the account code MUST be computed over the raw code bytes, not over any encoded or transformed representation. forall (account): encode_account(account).contains(keccak256(account.code)) where the hash occupies the fourth tuple position.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Contract creation","Code deployment"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker deploying a contract with specific bytecode can exercise this path. If the code hash is computed over a different representation (e.g., RLP-encoded code instead of raw bytes), the resulting hash differs, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect code hash computation would cause every account with code to have a different state representation across implementations, leading to a consensus split on any block containing contract deployments or code-touching operations.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC should deploy a contract and show the divergent code hash between faulty and correct implementations."},{"id":"PROP-0005","text":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT MUST be a module-level constant that is frozen and immutable after construction. Any attempt to modify EMPTY_ACCOUNT.nonce, EMPTY_ACCOUNT.balance, or EMPTY_ACCOUNT.code after module initialization MUST raise an error.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-028","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:EMPTY_ACCOUNT","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT is used as a reference value throughout state transition logic. If it is mutable and an internal code path modifies it, all subsequent comparisons against EMPTY_ACCOUNT would be incorrect. While not directly attacker-triggered, a mutation could be triggered indirectly through state transitions initiated by attacker transactions."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"If EMPTY_ACCOUNT is mutable and becomes corrupted, the definition of an empty account changes globally, potentially causing accounts to appear non-empty or vice versa. This affects account existence checks, which are consensus-critical.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires internal mutation; not directly exploitable by external attacker, but could be a latent bug enabling other attacks."},{"id":"PROP-0006","text":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT MUST have nonce == Uint(0), balance == U256(0), and code == b''. These values MUST be exactly equal to their zero/empty equivalents, not merely falsy or default-initialized.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-028","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:EMPTY_ACCOUNT","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT is compared against actual account states to determine if an account is empty (for deletion under EIP-161). If any field deviates from the specification, empty account detection fails, affecting state pruning and gas accounting."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect EMPTY_ACCOUNT field values would cause incorrect empty account detection. This affects state cleanup (EIP-161) and could lead to state bloat or incorrect gas accounting, but the impact is bounded to correctness rather than fund safety.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},{"id":"PROP-0007","text":"The type alias Address MUST be exactly Bytes20 (20 bytes). Any value assigned to an Address-typed variable MUST be exactly 20 bytes in length. Truncation or padding MUST NOT occur silently.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Address","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-external-user"],"edges":["tb-014"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Address parsing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Addresses are present in every transaction (from, to fields). An attacker crafting a transaction with a malformed address that is silently truncated or padded could cause the transaction to target a different account than intended. In Python reference specs, type aliases do not enforce runtime constraints unless explicitly checked."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Silent truncation or padding of addresses could redirect transactions to unintended accounts, potentially enabling fund theft. While the reference spec uses Python type hints that may not enforce runtime constraints, production implementations must enforce the 20-byte constraint.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate an implementation where a non-20-byte value passes as a valid Address and causes incorrect behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0008","text":"The type aliases Root and VersionedHash MUST both be exactly Hash32 (32 bytes). Root values represent Merkle tree roots and VersionedHash values represent blob commitment hashes. Any value shorter or longer than 32 bytes MUST be rejected.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Root,VersionedHash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie","actor-blob-submitter"],"edges":["tb-019","tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Block validation","Blob verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"VersionedHash values appear in type-3 blob transactions and are validated against blob KZG commitments. Root values appear in block headers (state_root, receipts_root). If either alias accepts non-32-byte values, downstream Merkle verification or commitment checks could be bypassed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Non-32-byte Root or VersionedHash values could bypass Merkle proof verification or blob commitment checks, potentially enabling state root forgery or blob data manipulation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate a path where a non-32-byte value is accepted as Root or VersionedHash."},{"id":"PROP-0009","text":"The type alias Bloom MUST be exactly Bytes256 (256 bytes). Bloom filter values in transaction receipts MUST be exactly 256 bytes. Incorrect Bloom size would cause log filtering to produce incorrect results.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Bloom","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Receipt generation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Bloom filters are generated from event logs during transaction execution. While the Bloom itself is derived (not directly attacker-controlled), an incorrect Bloom size would cause receipt encoding differences and state root divergence."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect Bloom size would cause receipt encoding differences, leading to receipts_root divergence and consensus failure. However, Bloom values are computed internally rather than directly supplied by an attacker.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate that a non-256-byte Bloom value is produced and accepted in receipt encoding."},{"id":"PROP-0010","text":"The Authorization dataclass for EIP-7702 MUST include chain_id for replay protection. forall (auth: Authorization): auth.chain_id == CURRENT_CHAIN_ID || auth.chain_id == 0 (wildcard). An Authorization with a chain_id that does not match the current chain and is not the wildcard value MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.chain_id","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit EIP-7702 set-code transactions with arbitrary Authorization tuples. If chain_id validation is missing or incorrect, authorizations from one chain could be replayed on another chain, allowing an attacker to set code on an account without the owner's consent on the target chain."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing chain_id validation enables cross-chain replay attacks for EIP-7702 authorizations. An attacker could replay a legitimate authorization from one chain to set arbitrary code on the victim's account on a different chain, enabling fund theft.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate cross-chain replay of an EIP-7702 authorization that sets code on a victim account."},{"id":"PROP-0011","text":"The (y_parity, r, s) fields of an Authorization MUST form a valid ECDSA signature over the authorization tuple (chain_id, address, nonce). The recovered signer address MUST be the account owner. An Authorization with an invalid signature MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.signature","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature recovery","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit transactions containing Authorization tuples with forged signatures. If ECDSA verification is missing or flawed, the attacker could set arbitrary code on any account without the owner's private key."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing ECDSA signature verification for EIP-7702 authorizations would allow an attacker to set arbitrary code on any account, enabling complete fund theft for all accounts on the chain.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate setting code on an account without a valid signature from the account owner."},{"id":"PROP-0012","text":"The nonce field in an Authorization MUST match the current nonce of the authorizing account at the time of execution. forall (auth: Authorization, account: Account): auth.nonce == account.nonce. An Authorization with a stale or future nonce MUST be rejected to prevent replay attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.nonce","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Nonce verification","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can replay a previously valid Authorization tuple. If nonce checking is absent, a single authorization could be replayed indefinitely to re-set code on the victim's account, even after the victim has revoked the authorization by incrementing their nonce."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing nonce validation enables same-chain replay of EIP-7702 authorizations. An attacker who obtains any valid authorization (even one the victim intended to be one-time) could repeatedly set code on the victim's account, enabling persistent fund theft.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate replaying a valid authorization after the account nonce has been incremented."},{"id":"PROP-0013","text":"The extract_deposit_data function MUST reject any input data whose length does not equal DEPOSIT_EVENT_LENGTH (576 bytes) by raising InvalidBlock. forall (data: bytes): len(data) != 576 => extract_deposit_data(data) raises InvalidBlock.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_validate_len","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The deposit contract emits events with data that is processed by extract_deposit_data. While the legitimate deposit contract always emits 576-byte data, a malicious contract at a spoofed address or a compromised deposit contract could emit non-standard data. Additionally, if DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS filtering is bypassed, arbitrary event data could reach this function."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"If non-576-byte data bypasses the length check, the subsequent offset and size parsing would read from incorrect positions, potentially producing malformed deposit requests that corrupt the beacon state (e.g., invalid pubkeys, wrong amounts). This is a consensus-critical path.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate crafting a deposit event with non-576-byte data that passes validation or causes unexpected behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0014","text":"All five offsets in extract_deposit_data MUST match their expected constant values: pubkey_offset == PUBKEY_OFFSET, withdrawal_credentials_offset == WITHDRAWAL_CREDENTIALS_OFFSET, amount_offset == AMOUNT_OFFSET, signature_offset == SIGNATURE_OFFSET, index_offset == INDEX_OFFSET. Any mismatch MUST raise InvalidBlock.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_check_pubkey_off,q_check_wc_off,q_check_amt_off,q_check_sig_off,q_check_idx_off","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker controlling or spoofing the deposit contract could emit events with valid-length data but incorrect internal offsets. If offset checks are missing or incomplete, the function would extract deposit fields from wrong positions, leading to corrupted deposit data accepted by the consensus layer."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect offsets would cause deposit fields (pubkey, withdrawal_credentials, amount, signature, index) to be extracted from wrong byte positions. This could create deposits with swapped or corrupted fields, leading to consensus-critical state corruption in the beacon chain.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that omitting or weakening an offset check allows extraction of deposit data from incorrect byte positions."},{"id":"PROP-0015","text":"All five sizes in extract_deposit_data MUST match their expected constant values: pubkey_size == 48, withdrawal_credentials_size == 32, amount_size == 8, signature_size == 96, index_size == 8. Any mismatch MUST raise InvalidBlock.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_check_pk_size,q_check_wc_size,q_check_amt_size,q_check_sig_size,q_check_idx_size","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker emitting deposit events with correct offsets but incorrect sizes could cause over-read or under-read of deposit fields. Missing size checks would allow the function to extract fields of incorrect length, producing malformed deposit requests."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"If a size check is bypassed, the extracted field would have an incorrect number of bytes. A wrong pubkey size (e.g., 47 instead of 48 bytes) would create an invalid BLS pubkey that could pass some but not all validation steps, causing consensus divergence between implementations with different tolerance for malformed pubkeys.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a size mismatch passes validation and produces a deposit request with incorrect field lengths."},{"id":"PROP-0016","text":"The output of extract_deposit_data MUST be exactly 192 bytes, consisting of pubkey(48) + withdrawal_credentials(32) + amount(8) + signature(96) + index(8) concatenated in that exact order. forall (data: valid_deposit_data): len(extract_deposit_data(data)) == 192.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_concat","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit data extraction","Consensus layer ingestion"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The concatenated 192-byte output is passed to the consensus layer as a deposit request. If the output length differs from 192, the consensus layer would parse the deposit request incorrectly, potentially misaligning pubkey, withdrawal_credentials, amount, signature, and index fields."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-192-byte deposit request output would cause the consensus layer to misparse all deposit fields, potentially crediting deposits to wrong validators with wrong amounts. This is a consensus-critical and fund-safety issue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that the output differs from 192 bytes or that field ordering is incorrect."},{"id":"PROP-0017","text":"Every validation failure path in extract_deposit_data MUST terminate with an InvalidBlock exception. There MUST be no code path where invalid data passes silently or produces a partial result. The function follows fail-stop semantics.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-005","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_error_len,q_error_pk_off,q_error_wc_off,q_error_amt_off,q_error_sig_off,q_error_idx_off,q_error_pk_size,q_error_wc_size,q_error_amt_size,q_error_sig_size,q_error_idx_size","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If any error path silently returns instead of raising InvalidBlock, the calling function (parse_deposit_requests) would accumulate malformed deposit data. The program graph shows 11 error states, each leading to q_final via an InvalidBlock raise. All 11 paths must be verified."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A validation bypass (silent return instead of InvalidBlock) on any of the 11 error paths would allow malformed deposit data to enter the consensus layer, potentially corrupting validator registrations.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must identify a specific error path that fails to raise InvalidBlock."},{"id":"PROP-0018","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST only process logs emitted by DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS. forall (log in receipt.logs): log.address != DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS => log is skipped entirely.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":"INV-006","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_addr","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can deploy a malicious contract that emits events with the same topic signature as the deposit contract. If the address filter is missing or uses case-insensitive comparison incorrectly, fake deposit events from the attacker's contract would be processed as legitimate deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing the deposit contract address filter would allow an attacker to inject arbitrary deposit requests by emitting matching events from any contract. This enables creating fake validator deposits, potentially corrupting the beacon state and stealing future rewards.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a deposit event from a non-deposit-contract address is processed as a valid deposit."},{"id":"PROP-0019","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST only process logs whose first topic matches DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH. forall (log from DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS): (len(log.topics) == 0 || log.topics[0] != DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH) => log is skipped.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-018","source_invariant_id":"INV-007","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_topic","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the deposit contract has other events (e.g., withdrawal events), and the topic filter is missing, non-deposit events from the deposit contract would be processed as deposits, producing garbage deposit data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Processing non-deposit events as deposit events would produce corrupted deposit requests with fields extracted from wrong event data. If the deposit contract emits other events, this could create invalid deposits.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must show that a non-DepositEvent log from the deposit contract is incorrectly processed as a deposit."},{"id":"PROP-0020","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST process receipts in receipt_keys order and logs within each receipt in their original order. The order of deposit requests in the output MUST be deterministic and match the order in which the underlying transactions were executed in the block.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-020","source_invariant_id":"INV-008","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_iter_keys,q_iter_logs","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If deposit ordering differs between implementations (e.g., due to non-deterministic receipt_keys iteration), the resulting deposit_requests bytes would differ, causing the requests_hash to diverge. This is a consensus-critical ordering property. An attacker could craft blocks with multiple deposit transactions to expose ordering bugs."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic deposit ordering would cause different nodes to compute different requests_hash values for the same block, leading to a consensus split. This is directly exploitable by including multiple deposit transactions in a single block.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that two valid implementations produce different deposit orderings for the same block."},{"id":"PROP-0021","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST accumulate deposit data without gaps. The deposit_requests output MUST be a contiguous concatenation of all valid 192-byte deposit request outputs. forall (valid_deposits d1, d2, ..., dn): deposit_requests == d1 + d2 + ... + dn with no interleaving, padding, or omission.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-009","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_append","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the accumulation has gaps (e.g., due to a failed extraction that does not propagate the InvalidBlock exception), the deposit_requests bytes would be shorter than expected, causing the consensus layer to misalign deposit field boundaries for all subsequent deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Gaps in deposit accumulation would cause all subsequent deposits in the same block to be misaligned, corrupting multiple validator registrations simultaneously. The impact scales with the number of deposits per block.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must show that a gap in accumulation causes subsequent deposit fields to be misaligned."},{"id":"PROP-0022","text":"trie_get MUST return a non-None receipt for every key in receipt_keys. forall (key in block_output.receipt_keys): trie_get(block_output.receipts_trie, key) != None. If any key yields a None receipt, the block MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-021","source_invariant_id":"INV-010","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_get_receipt","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipts trie integrity"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker proposing a block with a corrupted receipts trie could cause trie_get to return None for a valid key. If parse_deposit_requests does not handle this case (e.g., calling decode_receipt on None), it could crash the node or silently skip deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A None receipt for a valid key indicates receipts trie corruption. If not handled, this could crash the node (DoS) or cause silent deposit omission (consensus failure). The attacker can trigger this via a malformed block proposal.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a block with a corrupted receipts trie that causes parse_deposit_requests to crash or produce incorrect output."},{"id":"PROP-0023","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST individually SHA-256 hash each request before feeding the digest into the outer hash. The two-level hashing structure MUST be: outer = SHA256(SHA256(request_0).digest() || SHA256(request_1).digest() || ...). Single-level hashing (SHA256 of concatenated requests) is NOT equivalent.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash,q_update","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Request hash computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The requests hash is included in the execution payload header. If an implementation uses single-level hashing instead of two-level hashing, it would produce a different hash for the same requests, causing consensus divergence. An attacker can trigger this by including any request-generating transactions in a block."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect hashing structure would cause the execution payload header to contain a different requests_hash, leading to consensus divergence between implementations using single-level vs two-level hashing. This affects every block containing requests.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an implementation using a different hashing structure produces a divergent requests_hash."},{"id":"PROP-0024","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST be order-dependent. forall (requests r1, r2): compute_requests_hash([r1, r2]) != compute_requests_hash([r2, r1]) (unless r1 == r2). Reordering requests MUST produce a different hash.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-012","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_iter","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Request ordering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If compute_requests_hash is order-independent (e.g., using XOR instead of sequential hashing), two implementations processing requests in different orders would produce the same hash despite having different request orderings. Combined with PROP-0020, this ensures deposit ordering is consensus-binding."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Order-independent hashing would allow block proposers to reorder requests without changing the hash, potentially front-running or reordering deposits for economic advantage while other validators compute the same hash.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate request reordering that produces the same hash due to order-independent computation."},{"id":"PROP-0025","text":"compute_requests_hash with an empty requests list MUST produce the SHA-256 digest of the empty input: SHA256('').digest() == bytes.fromhex('e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4649b934ca495991b7852b855'). This is the hash of nothing being updated into the hasher.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-013","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_return","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":["Block validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Blocks with no request-generating transactions will have an empty requests list. If the empty-input hash value is wrong (e.g., the implementation uses a different initial state or adds a length prefix), every requestless block would have an incorrect requests_hash."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An incorrect empty-input hash would cause consensus failure on every block that contains no requests. Since many blocks may have no deposits, this would be a persistent consensus split affecting a large fraction of blocks.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that the implementation produces a different hash for an empty requests list."},{"id":"PROP-0026","text":"The deposit contract address used in parse_deposit_requests MUST be the canonical DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS specified in the chain configuration. It MUST NOT be hardcoded incorrectly, read from an untrusted source, or vulnerable to address collision attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","source_threat_id":"stride-tampering-tb-015","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Chain configuration","Deposit contract verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the deposit contract address is misconfigured or can be overridden via external input, an attacker could redirect deposit processing to a contract they control, injecting arbitrary deposits into the beacon state."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"A wrong deposit contract address would cause either: (1) legitimate deposits to be ignored (DoS on staking), or (2) fake deposits from an attacker-controlled contract to be accepted (beacon state corruption, fake validator creation).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate misconfiguration or override of DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS leading to fake deposit injection."},{"id":"PROP-0027","text":"The DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH used in parse_deposit_requests MUST exactly match the keccak256 hash of the deposit event signature from the deposit contract ABI. An incorrect hash would cause all legitimate deposit events to be silently skipped.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-018","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":["Constant verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a hardcoded constant. If incorrect, it would cause a systematic failure to process deposits on the affected implementation. While not directly attacker-controlled, the impact is severe as it would prevent all staking deposits from being processed."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect event signature hash would silently skip ALL legitimate deposits, effectively breaking staking on the affected implementation. This would cause consensus divergence as other implementations correctly process deposits.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Not directly attacker-exploitable but would cause a consensus split if the constant is wrong in any implementation."},{"id":"PROP-0028","text":"forall (data: bytes, len(data) == 576): extract_deposit_data MUST either return exactly 192 bytes or raise InvalidBlock. There MUST be no third outcome (empty return, partial return, None, or exception other than InvalidBlock).","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004,INV-005","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_final","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This property combines INV-004 and INV-005 to ensure the function has exactly two possible outcomes. Any implementation bug that causes a third outcome (e.g., returning an empty bytes or a Python None) would corrupt the deposit accumulation in parse_deposit_requests."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A third outcome (neither 192 bytes nor InvalidBlock) would silently corrupt the deposit request stream, potentially causing cascading misalignment of all subsequent deposit fields.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a code path that reaches q_final without returning exactly 192 bytes and without raising InvalidBlock."},{"id":"PROP-0029","text":"The RLP encoding in encode_account MUST be deterministic. forall (account1, account2): account1 == account2 => encode_account(account1, storage_root) == encode_account(account2, storage_root). Two identical accounts with the same storage_root MUST produce byte-identical RLP encodings.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_encode","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","RLP encoding"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-deterministic RLP encoding would cause identical account states to produce different state roots across nodes. If any implementation uses non-canonical RLP encoding (e.g., different integer encoding, non-minimal length prefixes), the resulting state roots would diverge."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic RLP encoding would cause state root divergence on every block, leading to a persistent consensus split. This is a foundational invariant for Ethereum's state model.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate two identical accounts producing different RLP encodings."},{"id":"PROP-0030","text":"The EIP-7702 Authorization dataclass MUST be used exclusively for set-code transactions (type 4). It MUST NOT be valid in any other transaction type context. Implementations MUST reject Authorization tuples in non-EIP-7702 transaction types.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction type validation","EIP-7702 processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker could attempt to include Authorization tuples in legacy or EIP-1559 transactions. If the transaction type check is missing, the authorization processing logic might execute in an unintended context, potentially bypassing other validation checks."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Processing Authorization tuples in wrong transaction types could bypass transaction type-specific validation logic, potentially enabling unauthorized code setting or other unexpected behavior.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate Authorization processing in a non-EIP-7702 transaction type."},{"id":"PROP-0031","text":"The y_parity field of Authorization MUST be either 0 or 1 (U8 with domain {0, 1}). Any other value MUST be rejected during signature recovery. Implementations MUST NOT accept y_parity values > 1.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.y_parity","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature recovery"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can craft Authorization tuples with arbitrary y_parity values. If values > 1 are accepted, the ECDSA recovery could produce an unexpected public key, potentially recovering a different signer address."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"While invalid y_parity values would likely cause signature recovery to fail or produce an incorrect signer, some implementations might accept y_parity > 1 via modular reduction, potentially recovering a valid but incorrect signer address.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that y_parity > 1 leads to incorrect signer recovery."},{"id":"PROP-0032","text":"The r and s values of an Authorization MUST be in the range [1, SECP256K1_ORDER - 1]. Values of 0 or >= SECP256K1_ORDER MUST be rejected. Implementations MUST NOT perform modular reduction on out-of-range r or s values.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.r,Authorization.s","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit Authorization tuples with r=0, s=0, or values >= SECP256K1_ORDER. If these pass validation, the ECDSA signature recovery could produce degenerate results or match arbitrary accounts."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-range r or s values in ECDSA can lead to signature malleability or recovery of unintended signer addresses. In the context of EIP-7702, this could allow unauthorized code setting on victim accounts.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that out-of-range r or s leads to a valid-looking signer recovery."},{"id":"PROP-0033","text":"The receipts trie MUST be complete: for every transaction in the block, there MUST be a corresponding receipt in the trie. forall (tx_index in 0..len(block.transactions)-1): trie_get(receipts_trie, rlp_encode(tx_index)) != None.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-021","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_get_receipt","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipts trie verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"A block proposer could submit a block with a receipts trie that is missing entries. If receipt completeness is not validated before processing deposits, missing receipts could cause deposits from those transactions to be silently skipped."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An incomplete receipts trie would cause some deposit events to be missed, leading to consensus divergence between nodes that validate trie completeness and those that do not.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a block with a missing receipt that causes deposit omission."},{"id":"PROP-0034","text":"The decode_receipt function called in parse_deposit_requests MUST correctly decode the receipt and preserve all log entries with their addresses, topics, and data fields intact. Incorrect decoding would corrupt the deposit filtering logic.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_decode","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Receipt RLP decoding"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If decode_receipt misparses the RLP-encoded receipt (e.g., due to a bug in handling typed receipts or non-legacy receipt formats), the log entries could be corrupted or missing, causing deposit events to be silently skipped or misprocessed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Receipt decoding errors could cause all deposit events within the affected receipt to be missed or corrupted, leading to consensus divergence on blocks containing deposits in the affected receipt format.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a receipt format that causes decode_receipt to produce incorrect log entries."},{"id":"PROP-0035","text":"The offset validation in extract_deposit_data MUST read offsets as big-endian unsigned integers from the ABI-encoded event data. Endianness errors would cause all offset comparisons to fail, either rejecting all valid deposits or accepting invalid ones.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_read_offsets","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["ABI decoding","Endianness handling"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"ABI encoding uses big-endian for offsets. If an implementation reads offsets as little-endian, the offset values would be drastically different from the expected constants, causing either (1) all deposits to be rejected, or (2) offsets to coincidentally match incorrect constants, extracting data from wrong positions."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Endianness errors in offset parsing would cause systematic deposit processing failures. If offsets are read in wrong endianness, they would not match expected constants, rejecting all valid deposits on the affected implementation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an endianness error causes deposits to be systematically rejected or misprocessed."},{"id":"PROP-0036","text":"The concatenation order in extract_deposit_data MUST be exactly pubkey + withdrawal_credentials + amount + signature + index. Any reordering of these fields would produce a different 192-byte output that the consensus layer would parse incorrectly.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_concat","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction","Consensus layer ingestion"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The consensus layer expects deposit request fields in a specific order. If the EL concatenates them in a different order, the CL would parse the 192 bytes incorrectly, assigning the pubkey bytes to withdrawal_credentials, etc."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Field reordering in the deposit request output would cause the consensus layer to misassign all deposit fields, creating validators with wrong pubkeys, wrong withdrawal credentials, and wrong amounts. This is a consensus-critical and fund-safety issue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that field reordering causes the CL to parse deposits incorrectly."},{"id":"PROP-0037","text":"The SHA-256 implementation used in compute_requests_hash MUST conform to FIPS 180-4. Using a different hash function (e.g., keccak256), a different variant (e.g., SHA-224), or a non-conforming implementation would produce a different digest for the same input.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Using the wrong hash function would cause the requests_hash to differ from all other implementations, resulting in consensus failure on every block containing requests."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Wrong hash function causes a persistent consensus split on every block with requests. This is a catastrophic implementation error rather than an externally exploitable vulnerability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Implementation error; not directly attacker-exploitable but causes consensus divergence."},{"id":"PROP-0038","text":"The storage_root parameter in encode_account MUST be validated against the storage trie Merkle root. forall (account): encode_account(account, storage_root) implies storage_root == merkle_root(account.storage_trie). Using an incorrect storage_root would cause the account encoding to be inconsistent with the actual storage state.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-022","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","Storage trie computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the storage_root passed to encode_account does not match the actual Merkle root of the account's storage trie, the encoded account would have a wrong storage root, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"A mismatched storage_root causes the entire state root to be incorrect, leading to consensus failure. This can be triggered by any transaction that modifies storage.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a code path where storage_root diverges from the actual storage trie root."},{"id":"PROP-0039","text":"The hash collision resistance assumption for keccak256 used in encode_account MUST hold. If two different code bytecodes produce the same keccak256 hash, two accounts with different code would have identical RLP encodings, violating account uniqueness.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Keccak256 preimage resistance"],"bug_bounty_scope":"out-of-scope","notes":"This is a cryptographic assumption on keccak256. A practical collision would have catastrophic implications for Ethereum but is considered computationally infeasible. Breaking keccak256 is out of scope for the bug bounty program."},"exploitability":"theoretical","severity":"INFORMATIONAL","severity_justification":"Relies on the cryptographic hardness of keccak256 collision resistance. No practical attack is known. This is a foundational assumption, not a vulnerability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Cryptographic assumption; breaking keccak256 is out of scope."},{"id":"PROP-0040","text":"The SHA-256 hash collision resistance assumption in compute_requests_hash MUST hold. A collision in the inner SHA-256 (per-request hashing) would allow two different requests to produce the same digest, making them indistinguishable in the outer hash.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["SHA-256 preimage resistance"],"bug_bounty_scope":"out-of-scope","notes":"This is a cryptographic assumption on SHA-256. A practical collision or preimage attack on SHA-256 would be a breakthrough in cryptography. Out of scope for the bug bounty program."},"exploitability":"theoretical","severity":"INFORMATIONAL","severity_justification":"Relies on SHA-256 collision resistance. No practical attack is known. Foundational cryptographic assumption.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Cryptographic assumption; breaking SHA-256 is out of scope."},{"id":"PROP-0041","text":"In parse_deposit_requests, the log.topics array MUST be checked for non-empty length before accessing log.topics[0]. Accessing topics[0] on an empty topics array MUST NOT cause an out-of-bounds access or crash.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-007","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_topic","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Event log processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can deploy a contract at DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS (if address spoofing is possible) or an event with zero topics. If the topics length check is missing, accessing topics[0] on an empty array would cause an index-out-of-bounds error, potentially crashing the node."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An out-of-bounds access on log.topics would crash the node during block processing, causing a denial of service. If the crash occurs during consensus-critical processing, it could affect block finalization.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a log with empty topics from DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS that causes a crash."},{"id":"PROP-0042","text":"The authorization address field in Authorization MUST be a valid 20-byte Ethereum address (Address = Bytes20). It represents the code address that the authorizer wants to set on their account. An invalid or non-20-byte address MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.address","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Address validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can include an Authorization with a non-20-byte address. If accepted, the EIP-7702 code delegation would reference an invalid address, potentially causing undefined behavior when the delegated code is executed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"An invalid authorization address would cause undefined behavior during code delegation execution. The impact depends on how the implementation handles the invalid address (crash, wrong code lookup, or no-op).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a non-20-byte authorization address causes unexpected behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0043","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST process each request exactly once. No request MUST be hashed twice (which would effectively duplicate it) or skipped (which would effectively remove it). The iteration over the requests list MUST be exact.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-011,INV-012","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_iter","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the iteration logic has an off-by-one error (processing n-1 or n+1 requests instead of n), the resulting hash would be incorrect. This would cause consensus divergence for any block with a non-zero number of requests."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An off-by-one error in request iteration would cause the requests_hash to be incorrect for blocks with requests, leading to consensus divergence.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate an iteration error that produces an incorrect requests_hash."},{"id":"PROP-0044","text":"The nonce field in Authorization MUST be U64 (unsigned 64-bit integer). It MUST NOT overflow or wrap around. If the authorizing account's nonce exceeds U64_MAX, the authorization MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.nonce","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Nonce range validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"While U64_MAX is astronomically large and practically unreachable, implementations in languages without native U64 overflow protection (e.g., Python) must ensure the nonce comparison does not overflow."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"U64 overflow for nonces is practically unreachable. The property exists for completeness and to guard against implementation errors in languages with arbitrary-precision integers where U64 truncation might not be enforced.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Practically unreachable; U64_MAX transactions from a single account is infeasible."},{"id":"PROP-0045","text":"The chain_id field in Authorization MUST be U256 (unsigned 256-bit integer). However, chain_id == 0 is reserved as a wildcard meaning 'any chain'. Implementations MUST treat chain_id == 0 as valid on all chains, not as an invalid or default value.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.chain_id","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Chain ID verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If an implementation rejects chain_id == 0 as invalid, legitimate wildcard authorizations would fail. Conversely, if an implementation does not properly handle the wildcard semantics, it might apply chain-specific authorizations across chains."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect handling of chain_id == 0 wildcard could either deny legitimate authorizations (DoS on EIP-7702 users) or expand authorization scope beyond the user's intent.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate incorrect wildcard handling leading to denial or over-application of authorizations."},{"id":"PROP-0046","text":"In parse_deposit_requests, the address comparison log.address == DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS MUST be an exact 20-byte equality check. Case-insensitive comparison, checksum-based comparison, or any normalization MUST NOT be used, as Ethereum addresses are raw 20-byte values at the execution layer.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":"INV-006","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_addr","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the address comparison uses case-insensitive string comparison (e.g., comparing hex representations), an attacker might exploit case differences. At the EVM level, addresses are 20-byte values without case, but some implementations might convert to hex strings for comparison."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"In practice, EVM-level address comparison is byte-exact. However, implementations that convert to strings for comparison might introduce case sensitivity issues. The impact is either false positives (accepting non-deposit events) or false negatives (rejecting legitimate deposits).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate an address comparison implementation that incorrectly matches or rejects addresses."},{"id":"PROP-0047","text":"The extract_deposit_data validation checks MUST be performed in the exact order specified: (1) data length, (2) pubkey offset, (3) withdrawal_credentials offset, (4) amount offset, (5) signature offset, (6) index offset, (7) pubkey size, (8) withdrawal_credentials size, (9) amount size, (10) signature size, (11) index size. While reordering does not affect correctness, it affects which error message is raised first, which matters for consensus on error behavior.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-002,INV-003","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_validate_len through q_check_idx_size","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the validation order differs and the error behavior is consensus-relevant (e.g., if InvalidBlock carries different error codes that affect execution), reordering validations could cause consensus divergence on invalid deposits."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Validation ordering typically does not affect consensus because InvalidBlock always causes the block to be rejected regardless of the specific error. However, if error codes or gas accounting differ per error path, ordering could matter.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Low impact; validation ordering is typically not consensus-critical as all error paths produce the same outcome (block rejection)."},{"id":"PROP-0048","text":"encode_account MUST handle the edge case where code is empty (b''). keccak256(b'') MUST produce the well-known empty code hash 0xc5d2460186f7233c927e7db2dcc703c0e500b653ca82273b7bfad8045d85a470. Incorrect handling of empty code would cause all code-less accounts to have wrong state roots.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","Code hash computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Every externally-owned account (EOA) has empty code. If the empty code hash is incorrect, every EOA's account encoding would differ, causing state root divergence on every block that creates or modifies an EOA."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect empty code hash would affect every EOA on the chain, causing a catastrophic state root divergence affecting virtually every block. This is one of the most impactful possible bugs.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate the wrong empty code hash causing state root divergence."},{"id":"PROP-0049","text":"The RLP encoding in encode_account MUST use canonical RLP: integers MUST use minimal-length big-endian encoding (no leading zeros except for the value 0 which is encoded as empty bytes), and the tuple MUST use the list encoding prefix.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_encode","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["RLP encoding","State root computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-canonical RLP encoding (e.g., using leading zeros in integer encoding or non-minimal length prefixes) would produce a different byte sequence for the same account, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-canonical RLP would cause state root divergence for every account, affecting every block. This is a foundational encoding invariant for Ethereum.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate non-canonical RLP producing a different state root."},{"id":"PROP-0050","text":"The two-level hashing in compute_requests_hash MUST prevent length-extension attacks. Because each request is individually hashed before being fed into the outer hash, an attacker cannot extend a valid requests_hash with additional requests. The property holds: forall (requests R, additional A): compute_requests_hash(R) cannot be extended to compute_requests_hash(R + A) without recomputing from scratch.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash,q_update,q_return","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Requests hash verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"SHA-256 is vulnerable to length-extension attacks on single-level hashing. The two-level structure (hash each request individually, then hash the digests) mitigates this. If an implementation uses single-level hashing, length-extension attacks could allow forging requests_hash values."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"If single-level hashing is used instead of two-level, length-extension attacks could allow an attacker to append requests to a valid block's requests list while keeping the same requests_hash, potentially injecting unauthorized deposits or withdrawals.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a length-extension attack on a single-level hashing implementation."}],"metadata":{"timestamp":"2026-02-05T00:00:00Z","total_properties":50,"by_type":{"invariant":25,"pre-condition":14,"post-condition":6,"assumption":5},"by_severity":{"CRITICAL":16,"HIGH":20,"MEDIUM":8,"LOW":3,"INFORMATIONAL":3},"by_scope":{"in_scope":44,"out_of_scope":3,"conditional":3},"by_reachability":{"external-reachable":40,"internal-only":7,"api-only":0,"theoretical":3},"bug_bounty_eligible_count":38,"coverage":{"subgraphs_covered":{"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)":["PROP-0001","PROP-0002","PROP-0003","PROP-0004","PROP-0029","PROP-0038","PROP-0039","PROP-0048","PROP-0049"],"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)":["PROP-0005","PROP-0006"],"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)":["PROP-0007","PROP-0008","PROP-0009"],"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)":["PROP-0010","PROP-0011","PROP-0012","PROP-0030","PROP-0031","PROP-0032","PROP-0042","PROP-0044","PROP-0045"],"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)":["PROP-0013","PROP-0014","PROP-0015","PROP-0016","PROP-0017","PROP-0028","PROP-0035","PROP-0036","PROP-0047"],"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)":["PROP-0018","PROP-0019","PROP-0020","PROP-0021","PROP-0022","PROP-0026","PROP-0027","PROP-0033","PROP-0034","PROP-0041","PROP-0046"],"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)":["PROP-0023","PROP-0024","PROP-0025","PROP-0037","PROP-0040","PROP-0043","PROP-0050"]},"trust_boundaries_covered":["tb-014","tb-016","tb-018","tb-019","tb-020"],"assumptions_covered":["asm-017","asm-018","asm-019","asm-020","asm-021","asm-022","asm-023","asm-024","asm-025","asm-026","asm-027","asm-028","asm-029"],"invariants_covered":["fork_types/SG-001:INV-001","fork_types/SG-001:INV-002","fork_types/SG-001:INV-003","fork_types/SG-002:INV-001","fork_types/SG-002:INV-002","fork_types/SG-003:INV-001","fork_types/SG-003:INV-002","fork_types/SG-003:INV-003","fork_types/SG-004:INV-001","fork_types/SG-004:INV-002","fork_types/SG-004:INV-003","fork_types/SG-004:INV-004","requests/SG-001:INV-001","requests/SG-001:INV-002","requests/SG-001:INV-003","requests/SG-001:INV-004","requests/SG-001:INV-005","requests/SG-002:INV-006","requests/SG-002:INV-007","requests/SG-002:INV-008","requests/SG-002:INV-009","requests/SG-002:INV-010","requests/SG-003:INV-011","requests/SG-003:INV-012","requests/SG-003:INV-013"]},"quality_checklist":{"all_properties_have_reachability":true,"all_properties_have_severity":true,"all_properties_have_exploitability":true,"all_properties_have_bug_bounty_eligible":true,"all_boundary_edges_covered":true,"properties_prioritized_by_scope":true,"metadata_includes_statistics":true}},"id":"PROP-W4B5-1"}
{"id":"PROP-W5B14-1","text":"bytes_to_bls_field MUST reject any deserialized integer value that is greater than or equal to BLS_MODULUS. Accepting out-of-range values would produce invalid field elements, corrupting all downstream polynomial arithmetic, cell computation, and KZG proof generation.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-002","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-002","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:cell_to_coset_evals","nodes":["actor-blob-submitter","actor-block-proposer","actor-p2p-peer","actor-validator-node"],"edges":["tb-001","tb-002","tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Blob size check"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit blob data via type-3 transactions or send crafted cells via P2P gossip. Blob bytes are deserialized into field elements via bytes_to_bls_field in cell_to_coset_evals (SG-001). If the range check is missing, modular reduction silently corrupts data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Violation allows an attacker to inject invalid field elements into the polynomial commitment pipeline. This corrupts KZG proofs and cells, potentially causing consensus failures where valid-looking but incorrect data passes verification across the entire network.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires PoC demonstrating that an out-of-range blob byte sequence produces a cell that passes verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch but commits to incorrect data."}

{"id":"PROP-W4B13-67","text":"BlobSidecarsByRoot deprecated protocol transition period serve_range must be bounded: [max(current_epoch - MIN_EPOCHS_FOR_BLOB_SIDECARS_REQUESTS, DENEB_FORK_EPOCH), FULU_FORK_EPOCH). Only blobs from pre-Fulu epochs within this range may be served by root.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-002","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker requests blobs by root for post-Fulu blocks or very old blocks. Consistent epoch boundary handling is critical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Deprecated protocol handling issue. Impact limited to resource waste or minor inconsistency in transition period responses.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-68","text":"Peers must not be penalized for requesting blob sidecars by root from FULU_FORK_EPOCH during the transition period. The deprecated BlobSidecarsByRoot protocol must degrade gracefully without peer scoring penalties.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-010","source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-013:INV-003","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-013:blob_sidecars_by_root_deprecated","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-006"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Consistent with PROP-0049 for by-range variant. Both deprecated protocols must degrade identically."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Peer scoring penalties for deprecated protocol use during transition could fragment the network by disconnecting nodes running slightly older software.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate peer being penalized for legitimate deprecated by-root request during transition."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-69","text":"The DataColumnSidecarsByRange response count must not exceed count * NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS sidecars, where count is the requested number of slots. This provides an upper bound beyond the absolute MAX_REQUEST_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS limit.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"p2p:SG-008:INV-001","source_threat_id":null,"covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-008:data_column_sidecars_by_range","nodes":["actor-req-resp-client","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-003"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a tighter bound than MAX_REQUEST_DATA_COLUMN_SIDECARS for small count values. Both limits must be enforced."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Missing count-based upper bound could allow sending more sidecars than expected for the requested range, confusing response parsing on the receiver.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate response exceeding count * NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS for a small count value."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-70","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify that the data column sidecar's inclusion proof correctly links kzg_commitments to the block body via verify_data_column_sidecar_inclusion_proof. Failure of the inclusion proof check must result in REJECT.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-025","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_inclusion_proof","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker crafts a sidecar with an invalid inclusion proof that appears structurally valid. If the inclusion proof check is bypassable or uses wrong parameters, arbitrary data columns could be injected."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Bypassing inclusion proof verification allows injection of data columns not committed in any valid block, undermining data availability guarantees.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: craft sidecar with invalid inclusion proof that passes verification."}
{"id":"PROP-W4B13-71","text":"The gossip validation pipeline must verify KZG proofs for data column sidecars via verify_data_column_sidecar_kzg_proofs. Failure must result in REJECT. The KZG check must occur after structural validation and signature verification, but must not be skipped.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-004","source_invariant_id":null,"source_threat_id":"stride-002","covers":{"primary_element":"p2p:SG-006:q_check_kzg_proofs","nodes":["actor-p2p-peer","actor-beacon-node"],"edges":["tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Gossip validation pipeline (structural)","Gossip validation pipeline (signature)"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker modifies data column cells while keeping commitments and proofs valid-looking. If KZG verification is skipped or has implementation bugs, tampered data propagates."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Skipping or incorrectly implementing KZG proof verification allows tampered data columns to propagate through the gossip network, completely undermining data availability.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC: craft sidecar with tampered column data that passes KZG verification."}
{"status":"success","source_file":"outputs/01b_PARTIAL_W3B12_1770273241.json","_source_file":"outputs/01d_PARTIAL_W0B1_1770284080.json","properties_count":50,"severity_distribution":{"CRITICAL":20,"HIGH":20,"MEDIUM":6,"INFORMATIONAL":2,"LOW":2},"bug_bounty_scope":{"program_name":"Ethereum Fusaka Audit Contest","program_url":"https://audits.sherlock.xyz/contests/1140","inherited_from":"trust_model","in_scope_components":["Block Validation","State Transition","Consensus Logic","Execution Layer (EL)","Transaction Pool"],"out_of_scope_components":["JSON-RPC API","Beacon API","Infrastructure bugs"]},"properties":[{"id":"PROP-0001","text":"The RLP encoding of an Account MUST produce a tuple in the strict order (nonce, balance, storage_root, keccak256(code)). Any deviation in tuple ordering produces a distinct and incorrect encoding, causing consensus divergence on account state roots.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","State transition execution","Account storage update"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Account encoding is invoked during state transitions triggered by externally-submitted transactions. An attacker crafting transactions that modify account state (nonce, balance, code) can exercise this path. If the tuple ordering is wrong, the entire state root diverges from the canonical chain, causing a consensus split."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect RLP tuple ordering in encode_account would produce a different state root for all nodes running the affected implementation, causing a consensus split. This is a network-wide impact affecting chain finality.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an alternative tuple ordering produces a different state root accepted by the faulty implementation but rejected by the reference implementation."},{"id":"PROP-0002","text":"The input to encode_account MUST be a valid Account instance containing nonce (Uint), balance (U256), and code (bytes) fields. If any field is missing or of incorrect type, encode_account MUST raise an error rather than produce a partial or malformed encoding.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EVM execution","State transition"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker submitting a transaction that triggers contract creation or state modification exercises this code path. If an implementation passes a malformed Account object (e.g., missing a field), the encoding could silently produce incorrect output."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A malformed Account input that bypasses validation could produce an incorrect RLP encoding, leading to state root divergence. The impact is limited to implementations that fail to validate Account structure before encoding.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a code path where an invalid Account object reaches encode_account without prior validation."},{"id":"PROP-0003","text":"The storage_root parameter passed to encode_account MUST be exactly 32 bytes in length (Hash32). If storage_root has any other length, the RLP encoding MUST fail rather than encode a truncated or padded value.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EVM execution","Storage root computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The storage root is computed from the account's storage trie. If a bug in storage trie computation produces a non-32-byte root, and encode_account does not validate the length, the encoded account would be non-canonical."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A non-32-byte storage root would produce non-canonical account encoding, causing state root divergence and consensus failure. While the storage root computation itself has validation, a bug there combined with missing validation here creates a critical path.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires demonstrating a scenario where a non-32-byte value reaches the storage_root parameter."},{"id":"PROP-0004","text":"The keccak256 hash of the account code MUST be computed over the raw code bytes, not over any encoded or transformed representation. forall (account): encode_account(account).contains(keccak256(account.code)) where the hash occupies the fourth tuple position.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Contract creation","Code deployment"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker deploying a contract with specific bytecode can exercise this path. If the code hash is computed over a different representation (e.g., RLP-encoded code instead of raw bytes), the resulting hash differs, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect code hash computation would cause every account with code to have a different state representation across implementations, leading to a consensus split on any block containing contract deployments or code-touching operations.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC should deploy a contract and show the divergent code hash between faulty and correct implementations."},{"id":"PROP-0005","text":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT MUST be a module-level constant that is frozen and immutable after construction. Any attempt to modify EMPTY_ACCOUNT.nonce, EMPTY_ACCOUNT.balance, or EMPTY_ACCOUNT.code after module initialization MUST raise an error.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-028","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:EMPTY_ACCOUNT","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT is used as a reference value throughout state transition logic. If it is mutable and an internal code path modifies it, all subsequent comparisons against EMPTY_ACCOUNT would be incorrect. While not directly attacker-triggered, a mutation could be triggered indirectly through state transitions initiated by attacker transactions."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"If EMPTY_ACCOUNT is mutable and becomes corrupted, the definition of an empty account changes globally, potentially causing accounts to appear non-empty or vice versa. This affects account existence checks, which are consensus-critical.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Requires internal mutation; not directly exploitable by external attacker, but could be a latent bug enabling other attacks."},{"id":"PROP-0006","text":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT MUST have nonce == Uint(0), balance == U256(0), and code == b''. These values MUST be exactly equal to their zero/empty equivalents, not merely falsy or default-initialized.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-028","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:EMPTY_ACCOUNT","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"EMPTY_ACCOUNT is compared against actual account states to determine if an account is empty (for deletion under EIP-161). If any field deviates from the specification, empty account detection fails, affecting state pruning and gas accounting."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect EMPTY_ACCOUNT field values would cause incorrect empty account detection. This affects state cleanup (EIP-161) and could lead to state bloat or incorrect gas accounting, but the impact is bounded to correctness rather than fund safety.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":null},{"id":"PROP-0007","text":"The type alias Address MUST be exactly Bytes20 (20 bytes). Any value assigned to an Address-typed variable MUST be exactly 20 bytes in length. Truncation or padding MUST NOT occur silently.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Address","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-external-user"],"edges":["tb-014"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Address parsing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Addresses are present in every transaction (from, to fields). An attacker crafting a transaction with a malformed address that is silently truncated or padded could cause the transaction to target a different account than intended. In Python reference specs, type aliases do not enforce runtime constraints unless explicitly checked."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Silent truncation or padding of addresses could redirect transactions to unintended accounts, potentially enabling fund theft. While the reference spec uses Python type hints that may not enforce runtime constraints, production implementations must enforce the 20-byte constraint.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate an implementation where a non-20-byte value passes as a valid Address and causes incorrect behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0008","text":"The type aliases Root and VersionedHash MUST both be exactly Hash32 (32 bytes). Root values represent Merkle tree roots and VersionedHash values represent blob commitment hashes. Any value shorter or longer than 32 bytes MUST be rejected.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Root,VersionedHash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie","actor-blob-submitter"],"edges":["tb-019","tb-001"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Block validation","Blob verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"VersionedHash values appear in type-3 blob transactions and are validated against blob KZG commitments. Root values appear in block headers (state_root, receipts_root). If either alias accepts non-32-byte values, downstream Merkle verification or commitment checks could be bypassed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Non-32-byte Root or VersionedHash values could bypass Merkle proof verification or blob commitment checks, potentially enabling state root forgery or blob data manipulation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate a path where a non-32-byte value is accepted as Root or VersionedHash."},{"id":"PROP-0009","text":"The type alias Bloom MUST be exactly Bytes256 (256 bytes). Bloom filter values in transaction receipts MUST be exactly 256 bytes. Incorrect Bloom size would cause log filtering to produce incorrect results.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:Bloom","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Receipt generation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Bloom filters are generated from event logs during transaction execution. While the Bloom itself is derived (not directly attacker-controlled), an incorrect Bloom size would cause receipt encoding differences and state root divergence."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect Bloom size would cause receipt encoding differences, leading to receipts_root divergence and consensus failure. However, Bloom values are computed internally rather than directly supplied by an attacker.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"Demonstrate that a non-256-byte Bloom value is produced and accepted in receipt encoding."},{"id":"PROP-0010","text":"The Authorization dataclass for EIP-7702 MUST include chain_id for replay protection. forall (auth: Authorization): auth.chain_id == CURRENT_CHAIN_ID || auth.chain_id == 0 (wildcard). An Authorization with a chain_id that does not match the current chain and is not the wildcard value MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.chain_id","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit EIP-7702 set-code transactions with arbitrary Authorization tuples. If chain_id validation is missing or incorrect, authorizations from one chain could be replayed on another chain, allowing an attacker to set code on an account without the owner's consent on the target chain."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing chain_id validation enables cross-chain replay attacks for EIP-7702 authorizations. An attacker could replay a legitimate authorization from one chain to set arbitrary code on the victim's account on a different chain, enabling fund theft.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate cross-chain replay of an EIP-7702 authorization that sets code on a victim account."},{"id":"PROP-0011","text":"The (y_parity, r, s) fields of an Authorization MUST form a valid ECDSA signature over the authorization tuple (chain_id, address, nonce). The recovered signer address MUST be the account owner. An Authorization with an invalid signature MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.signature","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature recovery","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit transactions containing Authorization tuples with forged signatures. If ECDSA verification is missing or flawed, the attacker could set arbitrary code on any account without the owner's private key."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing ECDSA signature verification for EIP-7702 authorizations would allow an attacker to set arbitrary code on any account, enabling complete fund theft for all accounts on the chain.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate setting code on an account without a valid signature from the account owner."},{"id":"PROP-0012","text":"The nonce field in an Authorization MUST match the current nonce of the authorizing account at the time of execution. forall (auth: Authorization, account: Account): auth.nonce == account.nonce. An Authorization with a stale or future nonce MUST be rejected to prevent replay attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.nonce","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Nonce verification","EIP-7702 authorization processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can replay a previously valid Authorization tuple. If nonce checking is absent, a single authorization could be replayed indefinitely to re-set code on the victim's account, even after the victim has revoked the authorization by incrementing their nonce."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Missing nonce validation enables same-chain replay of EIP-7702 authorizations. An attacker who obtains any valid authorization (even one the victim intended to be one-time) could repeatedly set code on the victim's account, enabling persistent fund theft.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate replaying a valid authorization after the account nonce has been incremented."},{"id":"PROP-0013","text":"The extract_deposit_data function MUST reject any input data whose length does not equal DEPOSIT_EVENT_LENGTH (576 bytes) by raising InvalidBlock. forall (data: bytes): len(data) != 576 => extract_deposit_data(data) raises InvalidBlock.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_validate_len","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The deposit contract emits events with data that is processed by extract_deposit_data. While the legitimate deposit contract always emits 576-byte data, a malicious contract at a spoofed address or a compromised deposit contract could emit non-standard data. Additionally, if DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS filtering is bypassed, arbitrary event data could reach this function."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"If non-576-byte data bypasses the length check, the subsequent offset and size parsing would read from incorrect positions, potentially producing malformed deposit requests that corrupt the beacon state (e.g., invalid pubkeys, wrong amounts). This is a consensus-critical path.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate crafting a deposit event with non-576-byte data that passes validation or causes unexpected behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0014","text":"All five offsets in extract_deposit_data MUST match their expected constant values: pubkey_offset == PUBKEY_OFFSET, withdrawal_credentials_offset == WITHDRAWAL_CREDENTIALS_OFFSET, amount_offset == AMOUNT_OFFSET, signature_offset == SIGNATURE_OFFSET, index_offset == INDEX_OFFSET. Any mismatch MUST raise InvalidBlock.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_check_pubkey_off,q_check_wc_off,q_check_amt_off,q_check_sig_off,q_check_idx_off","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker controlling or spoofing the deposit contract could emit events with valid-length data but incorrect internal offsets. If offset checks are missing or incomplete, the function would extract deposit fields from wrong positions, leading to corrupted deposit data accepted by the consensus layer."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Incorrect offsets would cause deposit fields (pubkey, withdrawal_credentials, amount, signature, index) to be extracted from wrong byte positions. This could create deposits with swapped or corrupted fields, leading to consensus-critical state corruption in the beacon chain.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that omitting or weakening an offset check allows extraction of deposit data from incorrect byte positions."},{"id":"PROP-0015","text":"All five sizes in extract_deposit_data MUST match their expected constant values: pubkey_size == 48, withdrawal_credentials_size == 32, amount_size == 8, signature_size == 96, index_size == 8. Any mismatch MUST raise InvalidBlock.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_check_pk_size,q_check_wc_size,q_check_amt_size,q_check_sig_size,q_check_idx_size","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit contract event emission","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker emitting deposit events with correct offsets but incorrect sizes could cause over-read or under-read of deposit fields. Missing size checks would allow the function to extract fields of incorrect length, producing malformed deposit requests."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"If a size check is bypassed, the extracted field would have an incorrect number of bytes. A wrong pubkey size (e.g., 47 instead of 48 bytes) would create an invalid BLS pubkey that could pass some but not all validation steps, causing consensus divergence between implementations with different tolerance for malformed pubkeys.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a size mismatch passes validation and produces a deposit request with incorrect field lengths."},{"id":"PROP-0016","text":"The output of extract_deposit_data MUST be exactly 192 bytes, consisting of pubkey(48) + withdrawal_credentials(32) + amount(8) + signature(96) + index(8) concatenated in that exact order. forall (data: valid_deposit_data): len(extract_deposit_data(data)) == 192.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_concat","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit data extraction","Consensus layer ingestion"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The concatenated 192-byte output is passed to the consensus layer as a deposit request. If the output length differs from 192, the consensus layer would parse the deposit request incorrectly, potentially misaligning pubkey, withdrawal_credentials, amount, signature, and index fields."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-192-byte deposit request output would cause the consensus layer to misparse all deposit fields, potentially crediting deposits to wrong validators with wrong amounts. This is a consensus-critical and fund-safety issue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that the output differs from 192 bytes or that field ordering is incorrect."},{"id":"PROP-0017","text":"Every validation failure path in extract_deposit_data MUST terminate with an InvalidBlock exception. There MUST be no code path where invalid data passes silently or produces a partial result. The function follows fail-stop semantics.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-005","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_error_len,q_error_pk_off,q_error_wc_off,q_error_amt_off,q_error_sig_off,q_error_idx_off,q_error_pk_size,q_error_wc_size,q_error_amt_size,q_error_sig_size,q_error_idx_size","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If any error path silently returns instead of raising InvalidBlock, the calling function (parse_deposit_requests) would accumulate malformed deposit data. The program graph shows 11 error states, each leading to q_final via an InvalidBlock raise. All 11 paths must be verified."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A validation bypass (silent return instead of InvalidBlock) on any of the 11 error paths would allow malformed deposit data to enter the consensus layer, potentially corrupting validator registrations.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must identify a specific error path that fails to raise InvalidBlock."},{"id":"PROP-0018","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST only process logs emitted by DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS. forall (log in receipt.logs): log.address != DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS => log is skipped entirely.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":"INV-006","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_addr","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can deploy a malicious contract that emits events with the same topic signature as the deposit contract. If the address filter is missing or uses case-insensitive comparison incorrectly, fake deposit events from the attacker's contract would be processed as legitimate deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Bypassing the deposit contract address filter would allow an attacker to inject arbitrary deposit requests by emitting matching events from any contract. This enables creating fake validator deposits, potentially corrupting the beacon state and stealing future rewards.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a deposit event from a non-deposit-contract address is processed as a valid deposit."},{"id":"PROP-0019","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST only process logs whose first topic matches DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH. forall (log from DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS): (len(log.topics) == 0 || log.topics[0] != DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH) => log is skipped.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-018","source_invariant_id":"INV-007","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_topic","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the deposit contract has other events (e.g., withdrawal events), and the topic filter is missing, non-deposit events from the deposit contract would be processed as deposits, producing garbage deposit data."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Processing non-deposit events as deposit events would produce corrupted deposit requests with fields extracted from wrong event data. If the deposit contract emits other events, this could create invalid deposits.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must show that a non-DepositEvent log from the deposit contract is incorrectly processed as a deposit."},{"id":"PROP-0020","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST process receipts in receipt_keys order and logs within each receipt in their original order. The order of deposit requests in the output MUST be deterministic and match the order in which the underlying transactions were executed in the block.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-020","source_invariant_id":"INV-008","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_iter_keys,q_iter_logs","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipt processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If deposit ordering differs between implementations (e.g., due to non-deterministic receipt_keys iteration), the resulting deposit_requests bytes would differ, causing the requests_hash to diverge. This is a consensus-critical ordering property. An attacker could craft blocks with multiple deposit transactions to expose ordering bugs."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic deposit ordering would cause different nodes to compute different requests_hash values for the same block, leading to a consensus split. This is directly exploitable by including multiple deposit transactions in a single block.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that two valid implementations produce different deposit orderings for the same block."},{"id":"PROP-0021","text":"parse_deposit_requests MUST accumulate deposit data without gaps. The deposit_requests output MUST be a contiguous concatenation of all valid 192-byte deposit request outputs. forall (valid_deposits d1, d2, ..., dn): deposit_requests == d1 + d2 + ... + dn with no interleaving, padding, or omission.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-009","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_append","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction execution","Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the accumulation has gaps (e.g., due to a failed extraction that does not propagate the InvalidBlock exception), the deposit_requests bytes would be shorter than expected, causing the consensus layer to misalign deposit field boundaries for all subsequent deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Gaps in deposit accumulation would cause all subsequent deposits in the same block to be misaligned, corrupting multiple validator registrations simultaneously. The impact scales with the number of deposits per block.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must show that a gap in accumulation causes subsequent deposit fields to be misaligned."},{"id":"PROP-0022","text":"trie_get MUST return a non-None receipt for every key in receipt_keys. forall (key in block_output.receipt_keys): trie_get(block_output.receipts_trie, key) != None. If any key yields a None receipt, the block MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-021","source_invariant_id":"INV-010","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_get_receipt","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipts trie integrity"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker proposing a block with a corrupted receipts trie could cause trie_get to return None for a valid key. If parse_deposit_requests does not handle this case (e.g., calling decode_receipt on None), it could crash the node or silently skip deposits."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A None receipt for a valid key indicates receipts trie corruption. If not handled, this could crash the node (DoS) or cause silent deposit omission (consensus failure). The attacker can trigger this via a malformed block proposal.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a block with a corrupted receipts trie that causes parse_deposit_requests to crash or produce incorrect output."},{"id":"PROP-0023","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST individually SHA-256 hash each request before feeding the digest into the outer hash. The two-level hashing structure MUST be: outer = SHA256(SHA256(request_0).digest() || SHA256(request_1).digest() || ...). Single-level hashing (SHA256 of concatenated requests) is NOT equivalent.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash,q_update","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Request hash computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The requests hash is included in the execution payload header. If an implementation uses single-level hashing instead of two-level hashing, it would produce a different hash for the same requests, causing consensus divergence. An attacker can trigger this by including any request-generating transactions in a block."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect hashing structure would cause the execution payload header to contain a different requests_hash, leading to consensus divergence between implementations using single-level vs two-level hashing. This affects every block containing requests.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an implementation using a different hashing structure produces a divergent requests_hash."},{"id":"PROP-0024","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST be order-dependent. forall (requests r1, r2): compute_requests_hash([r1, r2]) != compute_requests_hash([r2, r1]) (unless r1 == r2). Reordering requests MUST produce a different hash.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-012","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_iter","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Request ordering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If compute_requests_hash is order-independent (e.g., using XOR instead of sequential hashing), two implementations processing requests in different orders would produce the same hash despite having different request orderings. Combined with PROP-0020, this ensures deposit ordering is consensus-binding."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Order-independent hashing would allow block proposers to reorder requests without changing the hash, potentially front-running or reordering deposits for economic advantage while other validators compute the same hash.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate request reordering that produces the same hash due to order-independent computation."},{"id":"PROP-0025","text":"compute_requests_hash with an empty requests list MUST produce the SHA-256 digest of the empty input: SHA256('').digest() == bytes.fromhex('e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4649b934ca495991b7852b855'). This is the hash of nothing being updated into the hasher.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-013","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_return","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":["Block validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Blocks with no request-generating transactions will have an empty requests list. If the empty-input hash value is wrong (e.g., the implementation uses a different initial state or adds a length prefix), every requestless block would have an incorrect requests_hash."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An incorrect empty-input hash would cause consensus failure on every block that contains no requests. Since many blocks may have no deposits, this would be a persistent consensus split affecting a large fraction of blocks.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that the implementation produces a different hash for an empty requests list."},{"id":"PROP-0026","text":"The deposit contract address used in parse_deposit_requests MUST be the canonical DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS specified in the chain configuration. It MUST NOT be hardcoded incorrectly, read from an untrusted source, or vulnerable to address collision attacks.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","source_threat_id":"stride-tampering-tb-015","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Chain configuration","Deposit contract verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the deposit contract address is misconfigured or can be overridden via external input, an attacker could redirect deposit processing to a contract they control, injecting arbitrary deposits into the beacon state."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"A wrong deposit contract address would cause either: (1) legitimate deposits to be ignored (DoS on staking), or (2) fake deposits from an attacker-controlled contract to be accepted (beacon state corruption, fake validator creation).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate misconfiguration or override of DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS leading to fake deposit injection."},{"id":"PROP-0027","text":"The DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH used in parse_deposit_requests MUST exactly match the keccak256 hash of the deposit event signature from the deposit contract ABI. An incorrect hash would cause all legitimate deposit events to be silently skipped.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-018","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:DEPOSIT_EVENT_SIGNATURE_HASH","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":["Constant verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This is a hardcoded constant. If incorrect, it would cause a systematic failure to process deposits on the affected implementation. While not directly attacker-controlled, the impact is severe as it would prevent all staking deposits from being processed."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect event signature hash would silently skip ALL legitimate deposits, effectively breaking staking on the affected implementation. This would cause consensus divergence as other implementations correctly process deposits.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Not directly attacker-exploitable but would cause a consensus split if the constant is wrong in any implementation."},{"id":"PROP-0028","text":"forall (data: bytes, len(data) == 576): extract_deposit_data MUST either return exactly 192 bytes or raise InvalidBlock. There MUST be no third outcome (empty return, partial return, None, or exception other than InvalidBlock).","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004,INV-005","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_final","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"This property combines INV-004 and INV-005 to ensure the function has exactly two possible outcomes. Any implementation bug that causes a third outcome (e.g., returning an empty bytes or a Python None) would corrupt the deposit accumulation in parse_deposit_requests."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"A third outcome (neither 192 bytes nor InvalidBlock) would silently corrupt the deposit request stream, potentially causing cascading misalignment of all subsequent deposit fields.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a code path that reaches q_final without returning exactly 192 bytes and without raising InvalidBlock."},{"id":"PROP-0029","text":"The RLP encoding in encode_account MUST be deterministic. forall (account1, account2): account1 == account2 => encode_account(account1, storage_root) == encode_account(account2, storage_root). Two identical accounts with the same storage_root MUST produce byte-identical RLP encodings.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_encode","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","RLP encoding"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-deterministic RLP encoding would cause identical account states to produce different state roots across nodes. If any implementation uses non-canonical RLP encoding (e.g., different integer encoding, non-minimal length prefixes), the resulting state roots would diverge."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-deterministic RLP encoding would cause state root divergence on every block, leading to a persistent consensus split. This is a foundational invariant for Ethereum's state model.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate two identical accounts producing different RLP encodings."},{"id":"PROP-0030","text":"The EIP-7702 Authorization dataclass MUST be used exclusively for set-code transactions (type 4). It MUST NOT be valid in any other transaction type context. Implementations MUST reject Authorization tuples in non-EIP-7702 transaction types.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction type validation","EIP-7702 processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker could attempt to include Authorization tuples in legacy or EIP-1559 transactions. If the transaction type check is missing, the authorization processing logic might execute in an unintended context, potentially bypassing other validation checks."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Processing Authorization tuples in wrong transaction types could bypass transaction type-specific validation logic, potentially enabling unauthorized code setting or other unexpected behavior.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate Authorization processing in a non-EIP-7702 transaction type."},{"id":"PROP-0031","text":"The y_parity field of Authorization MUST be either 0 or 1 (U8 with domain {0, 1}). Any other value MUST be rejected during signature recovery. Implementations MUST NOT accept y_parity values > 1.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.y_parity","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature recovery"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can craft Authorization tuples with arbitrary y_parity values. If values > 1 are accepted, the ECDSA recovery could produce an unexpected public key, potentially recovering a different signer address."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"While invalid y_parity values would likely cause signature recovery to fail or produce an incorrect signer, some implementations might accept y_parity > 1 via modular reduction, potentially recovering a valid but incorrect signer address.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that y_parity > 1 leads to incorrect signer recovery."},{"id":"PROP-0032","text":"The r and s values of an Authorization MUST be in the range [1, SECP256K1_ORDER - 1]. Values of 0 or >= SECP256K1_ORDER MUST be rejected. Implementations MUST NOT perform modular reduction on out-of-range r or s values.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-025","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.r,Authorization.s","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","ECDSA signature verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can submit Authorization tuples with r=0, s=0, or values >= SECP256K1_ORDER. If these pass validation, the ECDSA signature recovery could produce degenerate results or match arbitrary accounts."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Out-of-range r or s values in ECDSA can lead to signature malleability or recovery of unintended signer addresses. In the context of EIP-7702, this could allow unauthorized code setting on victim accounts.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that out-of-range r or s leads to a valid-looking signer recovery."},{"id":"PROP-0033","text":"The receipts trie MUST be complete: for every transaction in the block, there MUST be a corresponding receipt in the trie. forall (tx_index in 0..len(block.transactions)-1): trie_get(receipts_trie, rlp_encode(tx_index)) != None.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-021","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_get_receipt","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Receipts trie verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"A block proposer could submit a block with a receipts trie that is missing entries. If receipt completeness is not validated before processing deposits, missing receipts could cause deposits from those transactions to be silently skipped."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An incomplete receipts trie would cause some deposit events to be missed, leading to consensus divergence between nodes that validate trie completeness and those that do not.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a block with a missing receipt that causes deposit omission."},{"id":"PROP-0034","text":"The decode_receipt function called in parse_deposit_requests MUST correctly decode the receipt and preserve all log entries with their addresses, topics, and data fields intact. Incorrect decoding would corrupt the deposit filtering logic.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_decode","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Receipt RLP decoding"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If decode_receipt misparses the RLP-encoded receipt (e.g., due to a bug in handling typed receipts or non-legacy receipt formats), the log entries could be corrupted or missing, causing deposit events to be silently skipped or misprocessed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Receipt decoding errors could cause all deposit events within the affected receipt to be missed or corrupted, leading to consensus divergence on blocks containing deposits in the affected receipt format.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a receipt format that causes decode_receipt to produce incorrect log entries."},{"id":"PROP-0035","text":"The offset validation in extract_deposit_data MUST read offsets as big-endian unsigned integers from the ABI-encoded event data. Endianness errors would cause all offset comparisons to fail, either rejecting all valid deposits or accepting invalid ones.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-019","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_read_offsets","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["ABI decoding","Endianness handling"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"ABI encoding uses big-endian for offsets. If an implementation reads offsets as little-endian, the offset values would be drastically different from the expected constants, causing either (1) all deposits to be rejected, or (2) offsets to coincidentally match incorrect constants, extracting data from wrong positions."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"Endianness errors in offset parsing would cause systematic deposit processing failures. If offsets are read in wrong endianness, they would not match expected constants, rejecting all valid deposits on the affected implementation.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that an endianness error causes deposits to be systematically rejected or misprocessed."},{"id":"PROP-0036","text":"The concatenation order in extract_deposit_data MUST be exactly pubkey + withdrawal_credentials + amount + signature + index. Any reordering of these fields would produce a different 192-byte output that the consensus layer would parse incorrectly.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_concat","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction","Consensus layer ingestion"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"The consensus layer expects deposit request fields in a specific order. If the EL concatenates them in a different order, the CL would parse the 192 bytes incorrectly, assigning the pubkey bytes to withdrawal_credentials, etc."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Field reordering in the deposit request output would cause the consensus layer to misassign all deposit fields, creating validators with wrong pubkeys, wrong withdrawal credentials, and wrong amounts. This is a consensus-critical and fund-safety issue.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that field reordering causes the CL to parse deposits incorrectly."},{"id":"PROP-0037","text":"The SHA-256 implementation used in compute_requests_hash MUST conform to FIPS 180-4. Using a different hash function (e.g., keccak256), a different variant (e.g., SHA-224), or a non-conforming implementation would produce a different digest for the same input.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"internal-only","entry_points":["Internal"],"attacker_controlled":false,"validation_layers":[],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Using the wrong hash function would cause the requests_hash to differ from all other implementations, resulting in consensus failure on every block containing requests."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Wrong hash function causes a persistent consensus split on every block with requests. This is a catastrophic implementation error rather than an externally exploitable vulnerability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Implementation error; not directly attacker-exploitable but causes consensus divergence."},{"id":"PROP-0038","text":"The storage_root parameter in encode_account MUST be validated against the storage trie Merkle root. forall (account): encode_account(account, storage_root) implies storage_root == merkle_root(account.storage_trie). Using an incorrect storage_root would cause the account encoding to be inconsistent with the actual storage state.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-022","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:encode_account","nodes":["actor-state-trie","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","Storage trie computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the storage_root passed to encode_account does not match the actual Merkle root of the account's storage trie, the encoded account would have a wrong storage root, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"A mismatched storage_root causes the entire state root to be incorrect, leading to consensus failure. This can be triggered by any transaction that modifies storage.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a code path where storage_root diverges from the actual storage trie root."},{"id":"PROP-0039","text":"The hash collision resistance assumption for keccak256 used in encode_account MUST hold. If two different code bytecodes produce the same keccak256 hash, two accounts with different code would have identical RLP encodings, violating account uniqueness.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Keccak256 preimage resistance"],"bug_bounty_scope":"out-of-scope","notes":"This is a cryptographic assumption on keccak256. A practical collision would have catastrophic implications for Ethereum but is considered computationally infeasible. Breaking keccak256 is out of scope for the bug bounty program."},"exploitability":"theoretical","severity":"INFORMATIONAL","severity_justification":"Relies on the cryptographic hardness of keccak256 collision resistance. No practical attack is known. This is a foundational assumption, not a vulnerability.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Cryptographic assumption; breaking keccak256 is out of scope."},{"id":"PROP-0040","text":"The SHA-256 hash collision resistance assumption in compute_requests_hash MUST hold. A collision in the inner SHA-256 (per-request hashing) would allow two different requests to produce the same digest, making them indistinguishable in the outer hash.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-023","source_invariant_id":null,"source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["SHA-256 preimage resistance"],"bug_bounty_scope":"out-of-scope","notes":"This is a cryptographic assumption on SHA-256. A practical collision or preimage attack on SHA-256 would be a breakthrough in cryptography. Out of scope for the bug bounty program."},"exploitability":"theoretical","severity":"INFORMATIONAL","severity_justification":"Relies on SHA-256 collision resistance. No practical attack is known. Foundational cryptographic assumption.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Cryptographic assumption; breaking SHA-256 is out of scope."},{"id":"PROP-0041","text":"In parse_deposit_requests, the log.topics array MUST be checked for non-empty length before accessing log.topics[0]. Accessing topics[0] on an empty topics array MUST NOT cause an out-of-bounds access or crash.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-007","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_topic","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Event log processing"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can deploy a contract at DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS (if address spoofing is possible) or an event with zero topics. If the topics length check is missing, accessing topics[0] on an empty array would cause an index-out-of-bounds error, potentially crashing the node."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An out-of-bounds access on log.topics would crash the node during block processing, causing a denial of service. If the crash occurs during consensus-critical processing, it could affect block finalization.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a log with empty topics from DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS that causes a crash."},{"id":"PROP-0042","text":"The authorization address field in Authorization MUST be a valid 20-byte Ethereum address (Address = Bytes20). It represents the code address that the authorizer wants to set on their account. An invalid or non-20-byte address MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-027","source_invariant_id":"INV-001","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.address","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Address validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"An attacker can include an Authorization with a non-20-byte address. If accepted, the EIP-7702 code delegation would reference an invalid address, potentially causing undefined behavior when the delegated code is executed."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"An invalid authorization address would cause undefined behavior during code delegation execution. The impact depends on how the implementation handles the invalid address (crash, wrong code lookup, or no-op).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate that a non-20-byte authorization address causes unexpected behavior."},{"id":"PROP-0043","text":"compute_requests_hash MUST process each request exactly once. No request MUST be hashed twice (which would effectively duplicate it) or skipped (which would effectively remove it). The iteration over the requests list MUST be exact.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-011,INV-012","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_iter","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction","P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the iteration logic has an off-by-one error (processing n-1 or n+1 requests instead of n), the resulting hash would be incorrect. This would cause consensus divergence for any block with a non-zero number of requests."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"An off-by-one error in request iteration would cause the requests_hash to be incorrect for blocks with requests, leading to consensus divergence.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate an iteration error that produces an incorrect requests_hash."},{"id":"PROP-0044","text":"The nonce field in Authorization MUST be U64 (unsigned 64-bit integer). It MUST NOT overflow or wrap around. If the authorizing account's nonce exceeds U64_MAX, the authorization MUST be rejected.","type":"pre-condition","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-004","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.nonce","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Nonce range validation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"While U64_MAX is astronomically large and practically unreachable, implementations in languages without native U64 overflow protection (e.g., Python) must ensure the nonce comparison does not overflow."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"U64 overflow for nonces is practically unreachable. The property exists for completeness and to guard against implementation errors in languages with arbitrary-precision integers where U64 truncation might not be enforced.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Practically unreachable; U64_MAX transactions from a single account is infeasible."},{"id":"PROP-0045","text":"The chain_id field in Authorization MUST be U256 (unsigned 256-bit integer). However, chain_id == 0 is reserved as a wildcard meaning 'any chain'. Implementations MUST treat chain_id == 0 as valid on all chains, not as an invalid or default value.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-026","source_invariant_id":"INV-002","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-004:Authorization.chain_id","nodes":["actor-authorizer","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-018"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Transaction validation","Chain ID verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If an implementation rejects chain_id == 0 as invalid, legitimate wildcard authorizations would fail. Conversely, if an implementation does not properly handle the wildcard semantics, it might apply chain-specific authorizations across chains."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"Incorrect handling of chain_id == 0 wildcard could either deny legitimate authorizations (DoS on EIP-7702 users) or expand authorization scope beyond the user's intent.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate incorrect wildcard handling leading to denial or over-application of authorizations."},{"id":"PROP-0046","text":"In parse_deposit_requests, the address comparison log.address == DEPOSIT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS MUST be an exact 20-byte equality check. Case-insensitive comparison, checksum-based comparison, or any normalization MUST NOT be used, as Ethereum addresses are raw 20-byte values at the execution layer.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-017","source_invariant_id":"INV-006","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-002:q_check_addr","nodes":["actor-deposit-contract","actor-execution-client"],"edges":["tb-020"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Event log filtering"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the address comparison uses case-insensitive string comparison (e.g., comparing hex representations), an attacker might exploit case differences. At the EVM level, addresses are 20-byte values without case, but some implementations might convert to hex strings for comparison."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"MEDIUM","severity_justification":"In practice, EVM-level address comparison is byte-exact. However, implementations that convert to strings for comparison might introduce case sensitivity issues. The impact is either false positives (accepting non-deposit events) or false negatives (rejecting legitimate deposits).","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate an address comparison implementation that incorrectly matches or rejects addresses."},{"id":"PROP-0047","text":"The extract_deposit_data validation checks MUST be performed in the exact order specified: (1) data length, (2) pubkey offset, (3) withdrawal_credentials offset, (4) amount offset, (5) signature offset, (6) index offset, (7) pubkey size, (8) withdrawal_credentials size, (9) amount size, (10) signature size, (11) index size. While reordering does not affect correctness, it affects which error message is raised first, which matters for consensus on error behavior.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-002,INV-003","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_validate_len through q_check_idx_size","nodes":["actor-execution-client"],"edges":[],"is_boundary_edge":false},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Deposit data extraction"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"If the validation order differs and the error behavior is consensus-relevant (e.g., if InvalidBlock carries different error codes that affect execution), reordering validations could cause consensus divergence on invalid deposits."},"exploitability":"internal-bug","severity":"LOW","severity_justification":"Validation ordering typically does not affect consensus because InvalidBlock always causes the block to be rejected regardless of the specific error. However, if error codes or gas accounting differ per error path, ordering could matter.","bug_bounty_eligible":false,"bug_bounty_notes":"Low impact; validation ordering is typically not consensus-critical as all error paths produce the same outcome (block rejection)."},{"id":"PROP-0048","text":"encode_account MUST handle the edge case where code is empty (b''). keccak256(b'') MUST produce the well-known empty code hash 0xc5d2460186f7233c927e7db2dcc703c0e500b653ca82273b7bfad8045d85a470. Incorrect handling of empty code would cause all code-less accounts to have wrong state roots.","type":"post-condition","source_assumption_id":null,"source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_compute_hash","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["State transition","Code hash computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Every externally-owned account (EOA) has empty code. If the empty code hash is incorrect, every EOA's account encoding would differ, causing state root divergence on every block that creates or modifies an EOA."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"An incorrect empty code hash would affect every EOA on the chain, causing a catastrophic state root divergence affecting virtually every block. This is one of the most impactful possible bugs.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate the wrong empty code hash causing state root divergence."},{"id":"PROP-0049","text":"The RLP encoding in encode_account MUST use canonical RLP: integers MUST use minimal-length big-endian encoding (no leading zeros except for the value 0 which is encoded as empty bytes), and the tuple MUST use the list encoding prefix.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-024","source_invariant_id":"INV-003","source_subgraph":"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-001:q_encode","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-state-trie"],"edges":["tb-019"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["Transaction"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["RLP encoding","State root computation"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"Non-canonical RLP encoding (e.g., using leading zeros in integer encoding or non-minimal length prefixes) would produce a different byte sequence for the same account, causing state root divergence."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"CRITICAL","severity_justification":"Non-canonical RLP would cause state root divergence for every account, affecting every block. This is a foundational encoding invariant for Ethereum.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate non-canonical RLP producing a different state root."},{"id":"PROP-0050","text":"The two-level hashing in compute_requests_hash MUST prevent length-extension attacks. Because each request is individually hashed before being fed into the outer hash, an attacker cannot extend a valid requests_hash with additional requests. The property holds: forall (requests R, additional A): compute_requests_hash(R) cannot be extended to compute_requests_hash(R + A) without recomputing from scratch.","type":"invariant","source_assumption_id":"asm-029","source_invariant_id":"INV-011","source_subgraph":"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)","covers":{"primary_element":"SG-003:q_hash,q_update,q_return","nodes":["actor-execution-client","actor-consensus-layer"],"edges":["tb-016"],"is_boundary_edge":true},"reachability":{"classification":"external-reachable","entry_points":["P2P"],"attacker_controlled":true,"validation_layers":["Block validation","Requests hash verification"],"bug_bounty_scope":"in-scope","notes":"SHA-256 is vulnerable to length-extension attacks on single-level hashing. The two-level structure (hash each request individually, then hash the digests) mitigates this. If an implementation uses single-level hashing, length-extension attacks could allow forging requests_hash values."},"exploitability":"external-attack","severity":"HIGH","severity_justification":"If single-level hashing is used instead of two-level, length-extension attacks could allow an attacker to append requests to a valid block's requests list while keeping the same requests_hash, potentially injecting unauthorized deposits or withdrawals.","bug_bounty_eligible":true,"bug_bounty_notes":"PoC must demonstrate a length-extension attack on a single-level hashing implementation."}],"metadata":{"timestamp":"2026-02-05T00:00:00Z","total_properties":50,"by_type":{"invariant":25,"pre-condition":14,"post-condition":6,"assumption":5},"by_severity":{"CRITICAL":16,"HIGH":20,"MEDIUM":8,"LOW":3,"INFORMATIONAL":3},"by_scope":{"in_scope":44,"out_of_scope":3,"conditional":3},"by_reachability":{"external-reachable":40,"internal-only":7,"api-only":0,"theoretical":3},"bug_bounty_eligible_count":38,"coverage":{"subgraphs_covered":{"fork_types/SG-001 (encode_account)":["PROP-0001","PROP-0002","PROP-0003","PROP-0004","PROP-0029","PROP-0038","PROP-0039","PROP-0048","PROP-0049"],"fork_types/SG-002 (Account_construction)":["PROP-0005","PROP-0006"],"fork_types/SG-003 (module_type_definitions)":["PROP-0007","PROP-0008","PROP-0009"],"fork_types/SG-004 (Authorization_construction)":["PROP-0010","PROP-0011","PROP-0012","PROP-0030","PROP-0031","PROP-0032","PROP-0042","PROP-0044","PROP-0045"],"requests/SG-001 (extract_deposit_data)":["PROP-0013","PROP-0014","PROP-0015","PROP-0016","PROP-0017","PROP-0028","PROP-0035","PROP-0036","PROP-0047"],"requests/SG-002 (parse_deposit_requests)":["PROP-0018","PROP-0019","PROP-0020","PROP-0021","PROP-0022","PROP-0026","PROP-0027","PROP-0033","PROP-0034","PROP-0041","PROP-0046"],"requests/SG-003 (compute_requests_hash)":["PROP-0023","PROP-0024","PROP-0025","PROP-0037","PROP-0040","PROP-0043","PROP-0050"]},"trust_boundaries_covered":["tb-014","tb-016","tb-018","tb-019","tb-020"],"assumptions_covered":["asm-017","asm-018","asm-019","asm-020","asm-021","asm-022","asm-023","asm-024","asm-025","asm-026","asm-027","asm-028","asm-029"],"invariants_covered":["fork_types/SG-001:INV-001","fork_types/SG-001:INV-002","fork_types/SG-001:INV-003","fork_types/SG-002:INV-001","fork_types/SG-002:INV-002","fork_types/SG-003:INV-001","fork_types/SG-003:INV-002","fork_types/SG-003:INV-003","fork_types/SG-004:INV-001","fork_types/SG-004:INV-002","fork_types/SG-004:INV-003","fork_types/SG-004:INV-004","requests/SG-001:INV-001","requests/SG-001:INV-002","requests/SG-001:INV-003","requests/SG-001:INV-004","requests/SG-001:INV-005","requests/SG-002:INV-006","requests/SG-002:INV-007","requests/SG-002:INV-008","requests/SG-002:INV-009","requests/SG-002:INV-010","requests/SG-003:INV-011","requests/SG-003:INV-012","requests/SG-003:INV-013"]},"quality_checklist":{"all_properties_have_reachability":true,"all_properties_have_severity":true,"all_properties_have_exploitability":true,"all_properties_have_bug_bounty_eligible":true,"all_boundary_edges_covered":true,"properties_prioritized_by_scope":true,"metadata_includes_statistics":true}},"id":"PROP-W4B5-1"}

